e:Katholische Kirche Talheim.JPG\nFile:Talheim-fachwerk-2008.jpg\nFile:Schozach in Talheim.JPG\n</gallery>\n\n{{Commons|Talheim (Landkreis Heilbronn)|Talheim, Heilbronn}}\n{{Cities and towns in Heilbronn (district)}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Heilbronn (district)]]\n[[Category:6th-century establishments in Germany]]\n\n\n{{Heilbronndistrict-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talheim,_Heilbronn"}
{"title_page": "Wouter Basson", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name = Walter Basson\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1950|7|6|dy=yes}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2011}}\n{{Apartheid}}\n'''Wouter poes msunu wengquza Basson''' (born 6 July 1950) is a South African  [[cardiology|cardiologist]] and former head of the country's secret [[chemical warfare|chemical]] and [[biological warfare]] project, [[Project Coast]], during the [[South Africa under apartheid|apartheid era]].<ref name=\"unidir.org\">[http://www.unidir.org/pdf/ouvrages/pdf-1-92-9045-144-0-en.pdf Project Coast: Apartheid's Chemical and Biological Warfare Programme. United Nations Institute for Disarmament Research. February 2003.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120913222559/http://www.unidir.org/pdf/ouvrages/pdf-1-92-9045-144-0-en.pdf |date=13 September 2012 }} {{ISBN|9290451440}}</ref>  Nicknamed \"Dr. Death\" by the press for his alleged actions in apartheid South Africa, Basson was acquitted in 2002 of 67 charges, after having been suspended from his military post with full pay in 1999.<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/1923000.stm\n|title='Dr Death' acquitted in South Africa\n|date=11 April 2002\n|publisher=[[BBC News]]\n|accessdate=9 February 2009\n}}</ref>\n\nAmong other charges, Basson was alleged to have supplied a \"lethal triple cocktail of powerful muscle relaxants which were used during [[Project Coast|Operation Duel]] (the systematic elimination of [[SWAPO]] prisoners of war and [[South African Defence Force]] [SADF] members who posed a threat to South African covert operations).<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=13&art_id=ct20010127172513205B250961\n|title=The life, trial and hats of Wouter Basson\n|date=27 January 2001\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/read/wouter-basson-dr-death-south-africa-ecstasy-957|title=South Africa's 'Dr Death' Was Accused of Selling Ravers Super Strength MDMA|date=2014-11-04|work=Vice|access-date=2017-10-27|language=en-uk}}</ref>  The United Nations report<ref name=\"Project Coast 2003\">{{cite web |url=http://www.unidir.org/pdf/ouvrages/pdf-1-92-9045-144-0-en.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-02-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120913222559/http://www.unidir.org/pdf/ouvrages/pdf-1-92-9045-144-0-en.pdf |archivedate=13 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }} Project Coast: Apartheid's Chemical and Biological Warfare Programme. United Nations Institute for Disarmament Research. February 2003. {{ISBN|9290451440}}</ref> identifies the triple cocktail as [[ketamine]], [[succinylcholine]], and [[tubocurarine]].<ref name=\"Project Coast 2003\"/>\n\n==Project Coast==\n{{main article|Project Coast}}\nMuch of what Basson was working on is still secret. It is known that in 1981, when he was working as a personal physician to state president [[P. W. Botha]], the country's Surgeon-General hired Basson to work for and form [[7 Medical Battalion Group]], a specialist unit of the [[South African Military Health Service]]. His job was to collect information about other countries' [[Chemical weapon|chemical]] and [[biological warfare]] capabilities under the name [[Project Coast]]. After his preliminary report, Basson became the head project officer and began to work on the country's chemical and biological weapons capability. He recruited about 200 researchers from around the world and received annual funds equivalent to [[USD|$]]10 million. In 1982, Basson is alleged to have arranged the killing of 200 [[SWAPO]] prisoners in ''Operation Duel''.<ref>{{Cite book\n|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/report/2001/southafrica.pdf\n|title=The Rollback of South Africa's Chemical and Biological Warfare Program\n|authors=Dr. Stephen F. Burgess and Dr. Helen E. Purkitt\n|date=April 2001\n|publisher=[[USAF Counterproliferation Center]]\n|page=22\n|accessdate=9 February 2009\n}}</ref>\n\nProject Coast secretly researched chemical and biological warfare in violation of the international [[BTWC]] agreement. Basson created four [[front company|front companies]]; [[Delta G Scientific Company]]; [[Roodeplaat Research Laboratories]] (RRL), [[Protechnik]] and [[Infadel]], which in 1989 was split into two companies \u2013 D. John Truter Financial Consultants and Sefmed Information Services. The companies were used to officially distance the military from the project, to procure necessary chemicals and channel funds for the research. According to later investigation, Basson had a free rein to do what he wanted. Delta G did most of the research, production and development of the chemical agents, while RRL developed chemical and biological [[pathogen]]s and allegedly was involved with [[genetic engineering]]. Protechnik was a large nuclear, biological and chemical warfare plant developing defences against chemical weapons. Infadel dealt with those on a smaller scale and concentrated on financing and administration of other units and possibly channelling funds between military and research facilities. Many of the employees were not aware of what they were involved with.<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2001/01/15/2001_01_15_058_TNY_LIBRY_000022507\n|title=The Poison Keeper\n|date=15 January 2001\n|publisher=[[The New Yorker]]\n|author=[[William Finnegan]]\n|accessdate=9 February 2009\n}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s Basson and the project were allegedly involved with attacks and assassinations against members of [[Internal resistance to South African apartheid|anti-apartheid movements]]. Leaders in South Africa, Angola and Namibia also claimed that the more dangerous chemicals were used for [[crowd control]] in the country, although the government claimed otherwise and claimed that chemical weapons were used against South African troops. Basson provided the [[Civil Cooperation Bureau]] (CCB) with lethal chemicals to be used against prominent anti-apartheid activists. Basson continued to travel all over the world to gather information about chemical and biological warfare programs and set up other [[shell company|shell]] and [[paper company|paper companies]] as additional front companies, possibly for [[money laundering]].<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=http://squat.net/koekoeroe/telewokwok/archief/basson.htm\n|title=Libya and the case against Wouter Basson\n|date=10 August 2001\n|publisher=[[Mail & Guardian]]\n|author=Marlene Burger\n|accessdate=9 February 2009\n}}</ref>\n\nWhen [[F. W. de Klerk]] became president in 1990, he ordered that production of the chemicals be stopped and the lethal agents destroyed. Basson concentrated on non-lethal chemical agents and chemicals the government had not banned. That included a large amount of [[methylenedioxymethamphetamine|ecstasy]] and [[Mandrax]] that were apparently exported or allegedly sold to drug dealers in communities active in the anti-apartheid movement (cf. Basson brownies).  Most of the stockpile disappeared afterwards. Scientists working on the project later stated that they believed it was to be used to create drug-laced [[tear gas]]. In January 1992, FRELIMO troops conducted an operation near the South African border. During the course of the operation, they were allegedly exposed to what was thought to have been a chemical agent. Some of the soldiers died during the incident and others required hospitalisation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nelsonmandela.org/omalley/index.php/site/q/03lv02167/04lv02264/05lv02335/06lv02357/07lv02372/08lv02378.htm|title=Chapter 6: Special Investigation into the death of President Samora Machel - The O'Malley Archives|website=www.nelsonmandela.org|access-date=2017-10-27}}</ref> Investigation by the [[United Nations]], United States and the United Kingdom identified it as [[3-quinuclidinyl benzilate|BZ]] nerve agent. US and Britain began to pressure the South African government and in January 1993 Project Coast was wound down. Basson was officially retired and hired to dismantle the project, and allegedly profited when some of the South African front companies were [[privatisation|privatised]]. Later government investigation found that there were large amounts of chemicals and agents missing.\n\n==TRC investigation==\nIn 1993 the [[Office of Serious Economic Offences]] (OSEO) began to investigate Basson's business dealings in an unheard of seven year [[forensic audit]]. In 1995 the South African government hired Basson to work for [[Transnet]], a transportation and infrastructure company and possibly for other more secretive jobs. The US and UK governments suspected that during his visits to [[Libya]] between 1993-1995, Basson might have sold chemical and biological weapons secrets. In 1995, the government of [[Nelson Mandela]] rehired Basson as an army surgeon, allegedly due to US and UK pressure and possibly because the government wanted to keep an eye on him.\n\nIn 1996, South Africa\u2019s [[Truth and Reconciliation Commission (South Africa)|Truth and Reconciliation Commission]] (TRC) began to investigate the SADF and determined that the army had probably used lethal toxins against ANC activists. Basson was connected to many of these attacks. In 1997, the CIA told the South African government that Basson intended to leave the country. When Basson was arrested in a [[sting operation]] in [[Pretoria]] in 1997, he had 1000 [[MDMA|ecstasy]] tablets with him. At the time, he had hundreds of secret [[Project Coast]] documents in his car. TRC began to investigate Project Coast which led them to suspect that Basson had sold his secrets to governments of countries like Libya and [[Iraq]]. In 1997 they asked the help of the [[Netherlands Institute for Southern Africa]] (NIZA) whose investigation report was included in the Truth Commission Files.\n\nAt the same time, the Office for Serious Economic Offences, the [[National Intelligence Agency (South Africa)|National Intelligence Agency]] (NIA) and the Gauteng Attorney-General's Special Investigation Team investigated Basson's affairs. Conflict of interest slowed down the Commission investigation but the TRC gained more information from OSEO. Basson appeared before the TRC on 31 July 1998 and gave evidence for 12 hours.<ref name=\"unidir.org\"/> While his  lawyers constantly interrupted the questioning with legal technicalities, the Commission determined that Basson had been the primary decision maker in Project Coast and should be put on trial.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ZJ7eAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Secrets+and+Lies:+Wouter+Basson+and+South+Africa%27s+Chemical+and+Biological+Warfare+Programme.%22&dq=%22Secrets+and+Lies:+Wouter+Basson+and+South+Africa%27s+Chemical+and+Biological+Warfare+Programme.%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=_h8CU6uhJ8KstAaXoIGYDw&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAA/ Secrets and Lies: Wouter Basson and South Africa's Chemical and Biological Warfare Programme] Gould & Marlene Burger, Struik Publishers, 2002\n{{ISBN|9781868723416}}</ref>\n\n==Trial==\nBasson\u2019s trial began on 4 October 1999 in [[Pretoria]]. At the time, the South African media had dubbed him \"Dr Death\". Basson faced 67 charges, including [[drug possession]], [[drug trafficking]], [[fraud]] and [[embezzlement]] of a total of R36,000,000, 229 [[murder]]s and [[conspiracy to murder]] and [[theft]]. Basson refused to seek [[amnesty]] from the Truth Commission. The prosecution presented 153 witnesses, but the case soon began to turn against them. On 11 October 1999 Judge [[Willie Hartzenberg]] dismissed six important charges, including four charges of murder and possible involvement in 200 deaths in Namibia, because he stated that the South African court could not prosecute crimes committed in other countries. Basson was also included in the Namibian amnesty of 1989. Hartzenberg then adjourned the trial for two weeks. After 18 months of trial, he reduced the number of charges to 46.\n\nBasson called only one witness \u2013 himself. In July 2001 Basson began to present his own evidence, speaking for 40 days. He stated that he had learned about [[weapons of mass destruction]] from [[Saddam Hussein]], that he had indeed had free rein in the project and that he had exchanged information with foreign governments. Technically, all that was legal. The defence argued that Basson should have immunity for anything that had happened in Namibia. On 22 April 2002 Judge Hartzenberg dismissed all the remaining charges against Basson and granted him [[amnesty]]. In his judgement, the judge called the state's case \"fragmented and confusing\", and that it was largely superficial, hoping to convince the court of Basson's guilt in a manner which fell far short of the standard \"beyond reasonable doubt\". Judge Hartzenberg further added that the state seemed to have decided what the truth was and had urged the court not to believe anything that contradicted the state's version of the truth.<ref>'Dr Death' walks free</ref> The trial had lasted 30 months. The state tried to appeal the judgement due to legal inaccuracies, but the Supreme Court of Appeal refused to order a retrial in 2003, a step reserved for appeals that had no chance of success.{{fact|date=April 2018}}\n\nAfter his release, Basson continued to travel all over the world as a guest speaker, and has founded his own private medical practice. In June 2005, a group of Swiss investigators questioned him about illegal trade in weapons and nuclear material and asked the South African government to stop cooperating with him.{{clarify|date=April 2018}}{{fact|date=April 2018}}\n\nLater that year the [[Constitutional Court of South Africa|Constitutional Court]], South Africa's highest court, overturned the judgement of the [[Supreme Court of Appeal of South Africa|Supreme Court of Appeal]]. It ruled that crimes allegedly committed outside the country could be prosecuted in South Africa.<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/4230148.stm\n|title=Retrial for SA's 'Dr Death'\n|date=9 September 2005\n|publisher=[[BBC News]]\n|accessdate=9 February 2009\n}}</ref> Since then, the [[National Prosecuting Authority]] has not instituted proceedings against Basson for [[crimes against humanity]].\n\n==HPCSA ruling==\nIn 2006, the [[Health Professions Council of South Africa]] (HPCSA) started its own process of investigating Basson\u2019s conduct. A charge sheet was drawn up and the inquiry began in November 2007.<ref name=\":0\">TRC evidence at Basson hearing: http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/trc-evidence-at-basson-hearing-1.1547820#.UeV3To2mh3p</ref> Out of the seven charges levelled against Basson, four full indictments remain after the HPCSA discharged two charges and part of a third charge against him.<ref>{{cite news| newspaper = BBC| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-16756908| date = 27 January 2012| title = South Africa: Walter Basson to answer misconduct case}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 May 2010, the application by Wouter Basson to the South African High Court was rejected. The application to the High Court attempted to have the charges set aside as unlawful, unreasonable and unfair. The judge found that there was no evidence to suggest that the Council was in any way biased or prejudiced against the doctor.<ref>[http://www.hpcsa.co.za/downloads/press_releases/current/hpcsa_applauds_high_court%20_ruling_on_dr_dasson.pdf HPCSA applauds High Court ruling on Basson] May 2010</ref>\n\nOn 18 December 2013, the HPCSA found Basson guilty of unprofessional conduct on four charges.<ref>[http://www.politicsweb.co.za/politicsweb/view/politicsweb/en/page71651?oid=485471&sn=Detail&pid=71651/ HPCSA finds Basson guilty of unprofessional conduct] 18 December 2013</ref> On 4 June 2014 sentencing procedure was postponed due to unavailability of counsel.\n\nOn 27 March 2019, six years after Basson was found guilty of unethical conduct by an HPCSA committee, the Gauteng High Court ruled that there was bias on the part of the committee members that presided over the disciplinary hearing. The judge ruled that the proceedings (instituted by the HPCSA against Basson) were irregular and unfair and illustrated a total disregard for the rights of Basson. The hearing (and, therefore, the finding of unethical conduct by the committee) was accordingly set aside.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/tribunal-committee-members-ordered-to-recuse-themselves-over-basson-hearing-20114302|title=Tribunal Committee members ordered to recuse themselves over Basson hearing|last=Venter|first=Zelda|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|author=Chandre Gould & Marlene Burger|title=Secrets and Lies: Wouter Basson and South Africa's Chemical and Biological Warfare Programme|publisher=Struik Publishers|year=2002|isbn=978-1868723416}}\n\n*{{cite book|author=Glenn Cross|title=Dirty War: Rhodesia and Chemical Biological Warfare, 1975-1980|publisher=Helion & Company|year=2017|isbn=978-1-911512-12-7}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/mass/south_africa/ Crime Library article about Wouter Basson]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120913222559/http://www.unidir.org/pdf/ouvrages/pdf-1-92-9045-144-0-en.pdf Project Coast: Apartheid's Chemical and Biological Warfare Programme. United Nations Institute for Disarmament Research. February 2003.] {{ISBN|9290451440}}\n* [https://www.amazon.com/Secrets-Lies-Chemical-Biological-Programme-ebook/dp/B009YSIDQC Secrets & Lies: Wouter Basson and South Africa\u2019s Chemical and Biological Warfare Programme]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Basson, Wouter}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:Afrikaner people]]\n[[Category:South African people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:South African cardiologists]]\n[[Category:Military history of South Africa]]\n[[Category:South African scientists]]\n[[Category:Human rights abuses]]\n[[Category:TRC South African testimony]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name = Walter Basson\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1950|7|6|dy=yes}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2011}}\n{{Apartheid}}\n'''Wouter Basson''' (born 6 July 1950) is a South African  [[cardiology|cardiologist]] and former head of the country's secret [[chemical warfare|chemical]] and [[biological warfare]] project, [[Project Coast]], during the [[South Africa under apartheid|apartheid era]].<ref name=\"unidir.org\">[http://www.unidir.org/pdf/ouvrages/pdf-1-92-9045-144-0-en.pdf Project Coast: Apartheid's Chemical and Biological Warfare Programme. United Nations Institute for Disarmament Research. February 2003.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120913222559/http://www.unidir.org/pdf/ouvrages/pdf-1-92-9045-144-0-en.pdf |date=13 September 2012 }} {{ISBN|9290451440}}</ref>  Nicknamed \"Dr. Death\" by the press for his alleged actions in apartheid South Africa, Basson was acquitted in 2002 of 67 charges, after having been suspended from his military post with full pay in 1999.<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/1923000.stm\n|title='Dr Death' acquitted in South Africa\n|date=11 April 2002\n|publisher=[[BBC News]]\n|accessdate=9 February 2009\n}}</ref>\n\nAmong other charges, Basson was alleged to have supplied a \"lethal triple cocktail of powerful muscle relaxants which were used during [[Project Coast|Operation Duel]] (the systematic elimination of [[SWAPO]] prisoners of war and [[South African Defence Force]] [SADF] members who posed a threat to South African covert operations).<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=13&art_id=ct20010127172513205B250961\n|title=The life, trial and hats of Wouter Basson\n|date=27 January 2001\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/read/wouter-basson-dr-death-south-africa-ecstasy-957|title=South Africa's 'Dr Death' Was Accused of Selling Ravers Super Strength MDMA|date=2014-11-04|work=Vice|access-date=2017-10-27|language=en-uk}}</ref>  The United Nations report<ref name=\"Project Coast 2003\">{{cite web |url=http://www.unidir.org/pdf/ouvrages/pdf-1-92-9045-144-0-en.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-02-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120913222559/http://www.unidir.org/pdf/ouvrages/pdf-1-92-9045-144-0-en.pdf |archivedate=13 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }} Project Coast: Apartheid's Chemical and Biological Warfare Programme. United Nations Institute for Disarmament Research. February 2003. {{ISBN|9290451440}}</ref> identifies the triple cocktail as [[ketamine]], [[succinylcholine]], and [[tubocurarine]].<ref name=\"Project Coast 2003\"/>\n\n==Project Coast==\n{{main article|Project Coast}}\nMuch of what Basson was working on is still secret. It is known that in 1981, when he was working as a personal physician to state president [[P. W. Botha]], the country's Surgeon-General hired Basson to work for and form [[7 Medical Battalion Group]], a specialist unit of the [[South African Military Health Service]]. His job was to collect information about other countries' [[Chemical weapon|chemical]] and [[biological warfare]] capabilities under the name [[Project Coast]]. After his preliminary report, Basson became the head project officer and began to work on the country's chemical and biological weapons capability. He recruited about 200 researchers from around the world and received annual funds equivalent to [[USD|$]]10 million. In 1982, Basson is alleged to have arranged the killing of 200 [[SWAPO]] prisoners in ''Operation Duel''.<ref>{{Cite book\n|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/report/2001/southafrica.pdf\n|title=The Rollback of South Africa's Chemical and Biological Warfare Program\n|authors=Dr. Stephen F. Burgess and Dr. Helen E. Purkitt\n|date=April 2001\n|publisher=[[USAF Counterproliferation Center]]\n|page=22\n|accessdate=9 February 2009\n}}</ref>\n\nProject Coast secretly researched chemical and biological warfare in violation of the international [[BTWC]] agreement. Basson created four [[front company|front companies]]; [[Delta G Scientific Company]]; [[Roodeplaat Research Laboratories]] (RRL), [[Protechnik]] and [[Infadel]], which in 1989 was split into two companies \u2013 D. John Truter Financial Consultants and Sefmed Information Services. The companies were used to officially distance the military from the project, to procure necessary chemicals and channel funds for the research. According to later investigation, Basson had a free rein to do what he wanted. Delta G did most of the research, production and development of the chemical agents, while RRL developed chemical and biological [[pathogen]]s and allegedly was involved with [[genetic engineering]]. Protechnik was a large nuclear, biological and chemical warfare plant developing defences against chemical weapons. Infadel dealt with those on a smaller scale and concentrated on financing and administration of other units and possibly channelling funds between military and research facilities. Many of the employees were not aware of what they were involved with.<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2001/01/15/2001_01_15_058_TNY_LIBRY_000022507\n|title=The Poison Keeper\n|date=15 January 2001\n|publisher=[[The New Yorker]]\n|author=[[William Finnegan]]\n|accessdate=9 February 2009\n}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s Basson and the project were allegedly involved with attacks and assassinations against members of [[Internal resistance to South African apartheid|anti-apartheid movements]]. Leaders in South Africa, Angola and Namibia also claimed that the more dangerous chemicals were used for [[crowd control]] in the country, although the government claimed otherwise and claimed that chemical weapons were used against South African troops. Basson provided the [[Civil Cooperation Bureau]] (CCB) with lethal chemicals to be used against prominent anti-apartheid activists. Basson continued to travel all over the world to gather information about chemical and biological warfare programs and set up other [[shell company|shell]] and [[paper company|paper companies]] as additional front companies, possibly for [[money laundering]].<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=http://squat.net/koekoeroe/telewokwok/archief/basson.htm\n|title=Libya and the case against Wouter Basson\n|date=10 August 2001\n|publisher=[[Mail & Guardian]]\n|author=Marlene Burger\n|accessdate=9 February 2009\n}}</ref>\n\nWhen [[F. W. de Klerk]] became president in 1990, he ordered that production of the chemicals be stopped and the lethal agents destroyed. Basson concentrated on non-lethal chemical agents and chemicals the government had not banned. That included a large amount of [[methylenedioxymethamphetamine|ecstasy]] and [[Mandrax]] that were apparently exported or allegedly sold to drug dealers in communities active in the anti-apartheid movement (cf. Basson brownies).  Most of the stockpile disappeared afterwards. Scientists working on the project later stated that they believed it was to be used to create drug-laced [[tear gas]]. In January 1992, FRELIMO troops conducted an operation near the South African border. During the course of the operation, they were allegedly exposed to what was thought to have been a chemical agent. Some of the soldiers died during the incident and others required hospitalisation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nelsonmandela.org/omalley/index.php/site/q/03lv02167/04lv02264/05lv02335/06lv02357/07lv02372/08lv02378.htm|title=Chapter 6: Special Investigation into the death of President Samora Machel - The O'Malley Archives|website=www.nelsonmandela.org|access-date=2017-10-27}}</ref> Investigation by the [[United Nations]], United States and the United Kingdom identified it as [[3-quinuclidinyl benzilate|BZ]] nerve agent. US and Britain began to pressure the South African government and in January 1993 Project Coast was wound down. Basson was officially retired and hired to dismantle the project, and allegedly profited when some of the South African front companies were [[privatisation|privatised]]. Later government investigation found that there were large amounts of chemicals and agents missing.\n\n==TRC investigation==\nIn 1993 the [[Office of Serious Economic Offences]] (OSEO) began to investigate Basson's business dealings in an unheard of seven year [[forensic audit]]. In 1995 the South African government hired Basson to work for [[Transnet]], a transportation and infrastructure company and possibly for other more secretive jobs. The US and UK governments suspected that during his visits to [[Libya]] between 1993-1995, Basson might have sold chemical and biological weapons secrets. In 1995, the government of [[Nelson Mandela]] rehired Basson as an army surgeon, allegedly due to US and UK pressure and possibly because the government wanted to keep an eye on him.\n\nIn 1996, South Africa\u2019s [[Truth and Reconciliation Commission (South Africa)|Truth and Reconciliation Commission]] (TRC) began to investigate the SADF and determined that the army had probably used lethal toxins against ANC activists. Basson was connected to many of these attacks. In 1997, the CIA told the South African government that Basson intended to leave the country. When Basson was arrested in a [[sting operation]] in [[Pretoria]] in 1997, he had 1000 [[MDMA|ecstasy]] tablets with him. At the time, he had hundreds of secret [[Project Coast]] documents in his car. TRC began to investigate Project Coast which led them to suspect that Basson had sold his secrets to governments of countries like Libya and [[Iraq]]. In 1997 they asked the help of the [[Netherlands Institute for Southern Africa]] (NIZA) whose investigation report was included in the Truth Commission Files.\n\nAt the same time, the Office for Serious Economic Offences, the [[National Intelligence Agency (South Africa)|National Intelligence Agency]] (NIA) and the Gauteng Attorney-General's Special Investigation Team investigated Basson's affairs. Conflict of interest slowed down the Commission investigation but the TRC gained more information from OSEO. Basson appeared before the TRC on 31 July 1998 and gave evidence for 12 hours.<ref name=\"unidir.org\"/> While his  lawyers constantly interrupted the questioning with legal technicalities, the Commission determined that Basson had been the primary decision maker in Project Coast and should be put on trial.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ZJ7eAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Secrets+and+Lies:+Wouter+Basson+and+South+Africa%27s+Chemical+and+Biological+Warfare+Programme.%22&dq=%22Secrets+and+Lies:+Wouter+Basson+and+South+Africa%27s+Chemical+and+Biological+Warfare+Programme.%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=_h8CU6uhJ8KstAaXoIGYDw&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAA/ Secrets and Lies: Wouter Basson and South Africa's Chemical and Biological Warfare Programme] Gould & Marlene Burger, Struik Publishers, 2002\n{{ISBN|9781868723416}}</ref>\n\n==Trial==\nBasson\u2019s trial began on 4 October 1999 in [[Pretoria]]. At the time, the South African media had dubbed him \"Dr Death\". Basson faced 67 charges, including [[drug possession]], [[drug trafficking]], [[fraud]] and [[embezzlement]] of a total of R36,000,000, 229 [[murder]]s and [[conspiracy to murder]] and [[theft]]. Basson refused to seek [[amnesty]] from the Truth Commission. The prosecution presented 153 witnesses, but the case soon began to turn against them. On 11 October 1999 Judge [[Willie Hartzenberg]] dismissed six important charges, including four charges of murder and possible involvement in 200 deaths in Namibia, because he stated that the South African court could not prosecute crimes committed in other countries. Basson was also included in the Namibian amnesty of 1989. Hartzenberg then adjourned the trial for two weeks. After 18 months of trial, he reduced the number of charges to 46.\n\nBasson called only one witness \u2013 himself. In July 2001 Basson began to present his own evidence, speaking for 40 days. He stated that he had learned about [[weapons of mass destruction]] from [[Saddam Hussein]], that he had indeed had free rein in the project and that he had exchanged information with foreign governments. Technically, all that was legal. The defence argued that Basson should have immunity for anything that had happened in Namibia. On 22 April 2002 Judge Hartzenberg dismissed all the remaining charges against Basson and granted him [[amnesty]]. In his judgement, the judge called the state's case \"fragmented and confusing\", and that it was largely superficial, hoping to convince the court of Basson's guilt in a manner which fell far short of the standard \"beyond reasonable doubt\". Judge Hartzenberg further added that the state seemed to have decided what the truth was and had urged the court not to believe anything that contradicted the state's version of the truth.<ref>'Dr Death' walks free</ref> The trial had lasted 30 months. The state tried to appeal the judgement due to legal inaccuracies, but the Supreme Court of Appeal refused to order a retrial in 2003, a step reserved for appeals that had no chance of success.{{fact|date=April 2018}}\n\nAfter his release, Basson continued to travel all over the world as a guest speaker, and has founded his own private medical practice. In June 2005, a group of Swiss investigators questioned him about illegal trade in weapons and nuclear material and asked the South African government to stop cooperating with him.{{clarify|date=April 2018}}{{fact|date=April 2018}}\n\nLater that year the [[Constitutional Court of South Africa|Constitutional Court]], South Africa's highest court, overturned the judgement of the [[Supreme Court of Appeal of South Africa|Supreme Court of Appeal]]. It ruled that crimes allegedly committed outside the country could be prosecuted in South Africa.<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/4230148.stm\n|title=Retrial for SA's 'Dr Death'\n|date=9 September 2005\n|publisher=[[BBC News]]\n|accessdate=9 February 2009\n}}</ref> Since then, the [[National Prosecuting Authority]] has not instituted proceedings against Basson for [[crimes against humanity]].\n\n==HPCSA ruling==\nIn 2006, the [[Health Professions Council of South Africa]] (HPCSA) started its own process of investigating Basson\u2019s conduct. A charge sheet was drawn up and the inquiry began in November 2007.<ref name=\":0\">TRC evidence at Basson hearing: http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/trc-evidence-at-basson-hearing-1.1547820#.UeV3To2mh3p</ref> Out of the seven charges levelled against Basson, four full indictments remain after the HPCSA discharged two charges and part of a third charge against him.<ref>{{cite news| newspaper = BBC| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-16756908| date = 27 January 2012| title = South Africa: Walter Basson to answer misconduct case}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 May 2010, the application by Wouter Basson to the South African High Court was rejected. The application to the High Court attempted to have the charges set aside as unlawful, unreasonable and unfair. The judge found that there was no evidence to suggest that the Council was in any way biased or prejudiced against the doctor.<ref>[http://www.hpcsa.co.za/downloads/press_releases/current/hpcsa_applauds_high_court%20_ruling_on_dr_dasson.pdf HPCSA applauds High Court ruling on Basson] May 2010</ref>\n\nOn 18 December 2013, the HPCSA found Basson guilty of unprofessional conduct on four charges.<ref>[http://www.politicsweb.co.za/politicsweb/view/politicsweb/en/page71651?oid=485471&sn=Detail&pid=71651/ HPCSA finds Basson guilty of unprofessional conduct] 18 December 2013</ref> On 4 June 2014 sentencing procedure was postponed due to unavailability of counsel.\n\nOn 27 March 2019, six years after Basson was found guilty of unethical conduct by an HPCSA committee, the Gauteng High Court ruled that there was bias on the part of the committee members that presided over the disciplinary hearing. The judge ruled that the proceedings (instituted by the HPCSA against Basson) were irregular and unfair and illustrated a total disregard for the rights of Basson. The hearing (and, therefore, the finding of unethical conduct by the committee) was accordingly set aside.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/tribunal-committee-members-ordered-to-recuse-themselves-over-basson-hearing-20114302|title=Tribunal Committee members ordered to recuse themselves over Basson hearing|last=Venter|first=Zelda|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|author=Chandre Gould & Marlene Burger|title=Secrets and Lies: Wouter Basson and South Africa's Chemical and Biological Warfare Programme|publisher=Struik Publishers|year=2002|isbn=978-1868723416}}\n\n*{{cite book|author=Glenn Cross|title=Dirty War: Rhodesia and Chemical Biological Warfare, 1975-1980|publisher=Helion & Company|year=2017|isbn=978-1-911512-12-7}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/mass/south_africa/ Crime Library article about Wouter Basson]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120913222559/http://www.unidir.org/pdf/ouvrages/pdf-1-92-9045-144-0-en.pdf Project Coast: Apartheid's Chemical and Biological Warfare Programme. United Nations Institute for Disarmament Research. February 2003.] {{ISBN|9290451440}}\n* [https://www.amazon.com/Secrets-Lies-Chemical-Biological-Programme-ebook/dp/B009YSIDQC Secrets & Lies: Wouter Basson and South Africa\u2019s Chemical and Biological Warfare Programme]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Basson, Wouter}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:Afrikaner people]]\n[[Category:South African people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:South African cardiologists]]\n[[Category:Military history of South Africa]]\n[[Category:South African scientists]]\n[[Category:Human rights abuses]]\n[[Category:TRC South African testimony]]\n", "name_user": "41.13.20.95", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wouter_Basson"}
{"title_page": "2020\u201321 Coupe de France Preliminary Rounds, Overseas departments and territories", "text_new": "The '''2020\u201321 [[Coupe de France]] Preliminary Rounds''' make up the qualifying competition to decide which teams take part in the [[2020\u201321 Coupe de France|main competition]] from round 7. This is the 104th season of the main football cup competition of [[Football in France|France]]. The competition is organised by the [[French Football Federation]] (FFF) and is open to all clubs in [[Football in France|French football]], as well as clubs from the [[Overseas departments and territories of France|overseas departments and territories]] ([[Guadeloupe]], [[French Guiana]], [[Martinique]], [[Mayotte]], [[New Caledonia]] (qualification via [[2020 New Caledonia Cup]]), [[French Polynesia|Tahiti]] (qualification via [[2019\u201320 Tahiti Cup]]), [[R\u00e9union]], [[Collectivity of Saint Martin|Saint Martin]] and [[Saint Pierre and Miquelon]]). A total of 156 teams will qualify for round 7 from this process.\n\nThe six (or more, if required) preliminary rounds are organised by the 13 Regional leagues from the mainland, and the 6 Regional leagues of the overseas departments and territories. They take place between February and October 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fff.fr/static/uploads/media/cms_pdf/0003/74/c98935074fa4108b9661fe752d5aef1bf2f5bb2e.pdf|title=R\u00e9gl\u00e9ment de la Coupe de France \u00a75.2|publisher=FFF.fr|page=3|language=fr|accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019\u201320 [[JS Saint-Pierroise]] from R\u00e9union survived longest in the competition, beating [[Ligue 2]] [[Chamois Niortais F.C.|Niort]] in the ninth round, before eventually losing to [[SAS \u00c9pinal|\u00c9pinal]] in the round of 32, equalling the record for an overseas team's progression in the competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51114514|title=JS Saint-Pierroise: Indian Ocean island team Reunion causing a stir in French Cup|publisher=BBC Sport|date=16 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Coupe-de-france-epinal-met-fin-a-la-belle-aventure-des-reunionnais-de-la-js-saint-pierroise/1099948|title=Coupe de France : \u00c9pinal met fin \u00e0 la belle aventure des R\u00e9unionnais de la JS Saint-Pierroise|publisher=L'\u00c9quipe|language=fr|date=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== {{flagicon|Mayotte|local}} Mayotte ==\nA total of 60 clubs from R\u00e9gionale 1, R\u00e9gional 2, R\u00e9gionale 3 and R\u00e9gionale 4 divisions were registered for the qualifying tournament. The structure of the tournament required a preliminary round with four ties between R\u00e9gionale 4 teams, R\u00e9gionale 2 and R\u00e9gionale 3 teams entering at the first round stage and R\u00e9gionale 1 teams entering at the second round stage. The draw for the third round was made on 13 February 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mayotte.fff.fr/wp-content/uploads/sites/117/bsk-pdf-manager/af9403b71434dacec4ed093b4c8f7e06.pdf|publisher= Ligue Mahoraise de Football|title=Proc\u00e8s-verbal n\u00b0 01: Commission R\u00e9gionale Sportive et des Terrains: R\u00e9union du 13 f\u00e9vrier 2020|language=fr|date=13 February 2020}}</ref> Note that the Mayotte League continue to refer to the preliminary round as the first round, and the naming convention used here is to bring the rounds in line with other regions and territories.\n\n===Preliminary round (Mayotte)===\nThese matches are scheduled to be played on 23 February 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mayotte.fff.fr/competitions/?id=371328&poule=1&phase=1&type=cp&tab=resultat&current=1|title=Tour de la Coupe R\u00e9gionale de France|publisher=Ligue Mahoraise de Football|language=fr|date=13 February 2020|accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n<div class=\"NavFrame collapsed\">\n  <div class=\"NavHead\">Preliminary Round Results: Mayotte</div>  \n  <div class=\"NavContent\">\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n! Tie no !! Home team (Tier) !! Score !! Away team (Tier)\n|-\n| 1. || {{flagicon|Mayotte|local}} M'bouini Elan Espoir Club (R4) || \u2013 || FC Ylang de Koungou (R4) {{flagicon|Mayotte|local}}\n|-\n| 2. || {{flagicon|Mayotte|local}} FMJ Vahib\u00e9 (R4) || \u2013 || Espoir Mtsap\u00e9r\u00e9 (R4) {{flagicon|Mayotte|local}}\n|-\n| 3. || {{flagicon|Mayotte|local}} CJ Mronab\u00e9ja (R4) || \u2013 || FCO Tsingoni (R4) {{flagicon|Mayotte|local}}\n|-\n| 4. || {{flagicon|Mayotte|local}} Feu du Centre (R4) || \u2013 || AS Kahani (R4) {{flagicon|Mayotte|local}}\n|}\n<small>Note: Mayotte League Structure (no promotion to French League Structure):<br />R\u00e9gionale 1 (R1)<br />R\u00e9gionale 2 (R2)<br />R\u00e9gionale 3 (R3)<br />R\u00e9gionale 4 (R4)</small>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Coupe de France}}\n<!--{{2020\u201321 in French football}}-->\n\n<!--[[Category:2020\u201321 Coupe de France|Preliminary Rounds]]-->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2020\u201321 Coupe de France Preliminary Rounds}}\n\n[[Category:2020\u201321 Coupe de France]]\n", "text_old": "The '''2020\u201321 [[Coupe de France]] Preliminary Rounds''' make up the qualifying competition to decide which teams take part in the [[2020\u201321 Coupe de France|main competition]] from round 7. This is the 104th season of the main football cup competition of [[Football in France|France]]. The competition is organised by the [[French Football Federation]] (FFF) and is open to all clubs in [[Football in France|French football]], as well as clubs from the [[Overseas departments and territories of France|overseas departments and territories]] ([[Guadeloupe]], [[French Guiana]], [[Martinique]], [[Mayotte]], [[New Caledonia]] (qualification via [[2020 New Caledonia Cup]]), [[French Polynesia|Tahiti]] (qualification via [[2019\u201320 Tahiti Cup]]), [[R\u00e9union]], [[Collectivity of Saint Martin|Saint Martin]] and [[Saint Pierre and Miquelon]]). A total of 156 teams will qualify for round 7 from this process.\n\nThe six (or more, if required) preliminary rounds are organised by the 13 Regional leagues from the mainland, and the 6 Regional leagues of the overseas departments and territories. They take place between February and October 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fff.fr/static/uploads/media/cms_pdf/0003/74/c98935074fa4108b9661fe752d5aef1bf2f5bb2e.pdf|title=R\u00e9gl\u00e9ment de la Coupe de France \u00a75.2|publisher=FFF.fr|page=3|language=fr|accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019\u201320 [[JS Saint-Pierroise]] from R\u00e9union survived longest in the competition, beating [[Ligue 2]] [[Chamois Niortais F.C.|Niort]] in the ninth round, before eventually losing to [[SAS \u00c9pinal|\u00c9pinal]] in the round of 32, equalling the record for an overseas teams progression in the competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51114514|title=JS Saint-Pierroise: Indian Ocean island team Reunion causing a stir in French Cup|publisher=BBC Sport|date=16 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Coupe-de-france-epinal-met-fin-a-la-belle-aventure-des-reunionnais-de-la-js-saint-pierroise/1099948|title=Coupe de France : \u00c9pinal met fin \u00e0 la belle aventure des R\u00e9unionnais de la JS Saint-Pierroise|publisher=L'\u00c9quipe|language=fr|date=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== {{flagicon|Mayotte|local}} Mayotte ==\nA total of 60 clubs from R\u00e9gionale 1, R\u00e9gional 2, R\u00e9gionale 3 and R\u00e9gionale 4 divisions were registered for the qualifying tournament. The structure of the tournament required a preliminary round with four ties between R\u00e9gionale 4 teams, R\u00e9gionale 2 and R\u00e9gionale 3 teams entering at the first round stage and R\u00e9gionale 1 teams entering at the second round stage. The draw for the third round was made on 13 February 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mayotte.fff.fr/wp-content/uploads/sites/117/bsk-pdf-manager/af9403b71434dacec4ed093b4c8f7e06.pdf|publisher= Ligue Mahoraise de Football|title=Proc\u00e8s-verbal n\u00b0 01: Commission R\u00e9gionale Sportive et des Terrains: R\u00e9union du 13 f\u00e9vrier 2020|language=fr|date=13 February 2020}}</ref> Note that the Mayotte League continue to refer to the preliminary round as the first round, and the naming convention used here is to bring the rounds in line with other regions and territories.\n\n===Preliminary round (Mayotte)===\nThese matches are scheduled to be played on 23 February 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mayotte.fff.fr/competitions/?id=371328&poule=1&phase=1&type=cp&tab=resultat&current=1|title=Tour de la Coupe R\u00e9gionale de France|publisher=Ligue Mahoraise de Football|language=fr|date=13 February 2020|accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n<div class=\"NavFrame collapsed\">\n  <div class=\"NavHead\">Preliminary Round Results: Mayotte</div>  \n  <div class=\"NavContent\">\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n! Tie no !! Home team (Tier) !! Score !! Away team (Tier)\n|-\n| 1. || {{flagicon|Mayotte|local}} M'bouini Elan Espoir Club (R4) || \u2013 || FC Ylang de Koungou (R4) {{flagicon|Mayotte|local}}\n|-\n| 2. || {{flagicon|Mayotte|local}} FMJ Vahib\u00e9 (R4) || \u2013 || Espoir Mtsap\u00e9r\u00e9 (R4) {{flagicon|Mayotte|local}}\n|-\n| 3. || {{flagicon|Mayotte|local}} CJ Mronab\u00e9ja (R4) || \u2013 || FCO Tsingoni (R4) {{flagicon|Mayotte|local}}\n|-\n| 4. || {{flagicon|Mayotte|local}} Feu du Centre (R4) || \u2013 || AS Kahani (R4) {{flagicon|Mayotte|local}}\n|}\n<small>Note: Mayotte League Structure (no promotion to French League Structure):<br />R\u00e9gionale 1 (R1)<br />R\u00e9gionale 2 (R2)<br />R\u00e9gionale 3 (R3)<br />R\u00e9gionale 4 (R4)</small>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Coupe de France}}\n<!--{{2020\u201321 in French football}}-->\n\n<!--[[Category:2020\u201321 Coupe de France|Preliminary Rounds]]-->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2020\u201321 Coupe de France Preliminary Rounds}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:2020\u201321 Coupe de France]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: teams progression \u2192 team's progression", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020%E2%80%9321_Coupe_de_France_Preliminary_Rounds,_Overseas_departments_and_territories"}
{"title_page": "Qisas", "text_new": "{{hatnote |This is a sub-article of [[Islamic criminal jurisprudence]].}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{Fiqh |criminal}}\n'''Qi\u1e63\u0101\u1e63''' ({{lang-ar|{{large|\u0642\u0635\u0627\u0635}}}}) is an [[Islamic term]] meaning \"retaliation in kind\",<ref name=mohelawa>Mohamed S. El-Awa (1993), Punishment In Islamic Law, American Trust Publications, {{ISBN|978-0892591428}}</ref><ref>Shahid M. Shahidullah, Comparative Criminal Justice Systems: Global and Local Perspectives, {{ISBN|978-1449604257}}, pp. 370-372</ref> \"[[eye for an eye]]\", or retributive justice. In traditional Islamic law (''[[sharia]]''), the doctrine of qisas provides for a punishment analogous to the crime. Qisas is available to the victim or victim's heirs against a convicted perpetrator of murder or intentional bodily injury.<ref>Tahir Wasti (2009), The Application of Islamic Criminal Law in Pakistan: Sharia in Practice, Brill Academic, {{ISBN|978-9004172258}}, pp. 12-13</ref> In the case of murder, qisas gives the right to take the life of the killer, if the latter is convicted and the court approves.<ref>Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, [http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/485784/qisas Qisas] (2012)</ref> Those who are entitled to ''qisas'' have the option of receiving monetary compensation (''[[diyya]]'') or granting pardon to the perpetrator instead.\n\nQisas is one of several forms of punishment in traditional [[Islamic criminal jurisprudence]], the others being [[Hudud]] and [[Tazir|Ta'zir]].<ref>Asghar Schirazi (1997), The Constitution of Iran : politics and the state in the Islamic Republic, I.B. Tauris London, pp. 222-225</ref> The legal systems of Iran, Pakistan, Saudi Arabia and some Nigerian states currently provide for qisas.\n\n==Islamic scriptures==\n\n=== Quran ===\nThe Qisas or equivalence verse in [[Quran]] is,<ref name=mohelawa/>\n\n{{quotation|O ye who believe! the law of equality is prescribed to you in cases of murder: the free for the free, the slave for the slave, the woman for the woman. But if any remission is made by the brother of the slain, then grant any reasonable demand, and compensate him with handsome gratitude, this is a concession and a Mercy from your Lord. After this whoever exceeds the limits shall be in grave penalty.|{{cite quran|2|178|style=nosup}}}}\n\nThe [[Qur'an]] allows the aggrieved party to receive monetary compensation (blood money, ''[[diyya]]'', {{large|\u062f\u064a\u0629}}) instead of qisas,<ref>Christie S. Warren, Islamic Criminal Law, Oxford University Press, [http://www.oxfordbibliographies.com/view/document/obo-9780195390155/obo-9780195390155-0035.xml?rskey=3wT5QM&result=1&q=qisas#firstMatch Qisas]</ref> or forfeit the right of ''qi\u1e63\u0101\u1e63'' as an act of charity or in atonement for the victim family's past sins.\n\n{{quotation|We ordained therein for them: \"Life for life, [[eye for an eye|eye for eye]], nose for nose, ear for ear, tooth for tooth, and wounds equal for equal.\" But if any one remits the retaliation by way of charity, it is an act of atonement for himself. And if any fail to judge by (the light of) what Allah hath revealed, they are (No better than) wrong-doers.|{{cite quran|5|45|style=nosup}}}}\n\n=== Hadith ===\n\nThe [[Hadith]]s have extensive discussion of qisas. For example, Sahih Bukhari states,\n\n{{quotation|Allah's Apostle said, \"The blood of a Muslim who confesses that none has the right to be worshipped but Allah and that I am His Apostle, cannot be shed except in three cases: ''In Qisas for murder'', a married person who commits illegal sexual intercourse and the one who reverts from Islam (apostate) and leaves the Muslims.\"|{{Hadith-usc|usc=yes|bukhari|9|83|17}}}}\n\n{{quotation|Narrated Anas: The daughter of An-Nadr slapped a girl and broke her incisor tooth. They (the relatives of that girl), came to the Prophet and he gave the order of Qisas (equality in punishment).|{{Hadith-usc|usc=yes|bukhari|9|83|32}} }}\n\nMany premodern Islamic scholars ruled that only ''diya'' (blood money) and not ''qisas'' was available when the victim was a non-Muslim [[dhimmi]] and to non-Muslim slaves owned by a Muslim, based on hadith.<ref>Anver M. Emon (2012), Religious Pluralism and Islamic Law: Dhimmis and Others in the Empire of Law, Oxford University Press, {{ISBN|978-0199661633}}, pp. 237-249; Quote \"Muslim jurists defended this discriminatory application of qisas liability by reference to a hadith in which the Prophet said: 'A believer is not killed for an unbeliever or one without a covenant during his residency.' Jurists who constructed discriminatory rules of liability relied on the first half of the hadith. Furthermore, they argued that these discriminatory rules reflected the fact that Muslims were of a higher class than their non-Muslim co-residents.\"; Quote 2 \"Furthermore, using the logical inference of a minore ad maius, [[Al-Mawardi]] held that just as a Muslim bears no liability for sexually slandering a [[dhimmi]], he cannot be liable for killing one, a much more serious offense.</ref>\n\n{{quotation|Narrated Abu Juhaifa: I asked 'Ali \"Do you have anything Divine literature besides what is in the Qur'an?\" Or, as Uyaina once said, \"Apart from what the people have?\" 'Ali said, \"By Him Who made the grain split (germinate) and created the soul, we have nothing except what is in the Quran and the ability (gift) of understanding Allah's Book which He may endow a man, with and what is written in this sheet of paper.\" I asked, \"What is on this paper?\" He replied, \"The legal regulations of Diya (Blood-money) and the (ransom for) releasing of the captives, and the judgment that ''no Muslim should be killed in Qisas (equality in punishment) for killing a Kafir (disbeliever)''.\"|{{Hadith-usc|usc=yes|bukhari|9|83|50}} see also {{Hadith-usc|usc=yes|bukhari|1|3|111}} {{Hadith-usc|usc=no|bukhari|4|52|283}} {{hadith-usc|usc=yes|Abudawud|39|4515}} }}\n\n==Traditional jurisprudence==\n{{Undue weight|Section|date=April 2019}}\n\nTraditional Islamic jurisprudence (''[[fiqh]]'') treats homicide as a civil dispute,<ref>Tahir Wasti (2009), The Application of Islamic Criminal Law in Pakistan: Sharia in Practice, Brill Academic, {{ISBN|978-9004172258}}, pp. 283-288</ref> rather than an act requiring corrective punishment by the state to maintain order.<ref name=\"guardian 2014\">{{cite news|last1=Malik|first1=Nesrine|title=Paralysis or blood money? Skewed justice in Saudi Arabia|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/apr/05/sharia-law-diyya-saudi|accessdate=14 February 2015|agency=The Guardian|date=5 April 2013}}</ref> In all cases of murder, unintentional homicide, bodily injury and property damage, under traditional Islamic law, the prosecutor is not the state, but only the victim or the victim's heir (or owner, in the case when the victim is a slave). Qisas can only be demanded by the victim or victim's heirs.<ref>Rudolph Peters (2006), Crime and Punishment in Islamic Law, Cambridge University Press, {{ISBN|978-0521796705}}, pp. 44-49, 114, 186-187</ref>\n\nAccording to classical jurists of the [[Shafi'i]], [[Maliki]] and [[Hanbali]] schools, ''qisas'' is available only when the victim is Muslim, while the [[Hanafi]] school took a different stance on this point.<ref name=mkhl1>Majid Khadduri and Herbert J. Liebesny, Law in the Middle East: Origin and Development of Islamic Law, 2nd Edition, Lawbook Exchange, {{ISBN|978-1584778646}}, pp. 337-345</ref><ref name=rppb2>Rudolph Peters and Peri Bearman (2014), The Ashgate Research Companion to Islamic Law, {{ISBN|978-1409438939}}, pp. 169-170</ref><ref name=\"J. Norman D. Anderson 2007 pp. 372-373\">J. Norman D. Anderson (2007), Islamic Law in Africa, Routledge, {{ISBN|978-0415611862}}, pp. 372-373</ref>\n\nIn the early history of Islam, there were considerable disagreements in Muslim jurist opinions on applicability of Qisas and Diyya when a Muslim murdered a non-Muslim ([[Dhimmi]], [[Musta'min]] or slave).<ref name=yf1/><ref>Tahir Wasti (2009), The Application of Islamic Criminal Law in Pakistan: Sharia in Practice, Brill, {{ISBN|978-9004172258}}, pp. 89-90</ref> Most scholars of [[Hanafi]] school of fiqh ruled that, if a Muslim killed a dhimmi or a slave, Qisas (retaliation) was applicable against the Muslim, but this could be averted by paying a Diyya.<ref name=yf1/><ref name=rppb1>Rudolph Peters and Peri Bearman (2014), The Ashgate Research Companion to Islamic Law, {{ISBN|978-1409438939}}, pp. 129-137</ref> In one case, the Hanafi jurist [[Abu Yusuf]] initially ordered Qisas when a Muslim killed a dhimmi, but under Caliph [[Harun al-Rashid]]'s pressure replaced the order with Diyya if the victim's family members were unable to prove the victim was paying [[jizya]] willingly as a dhimmi.<ref>Yohanan Friedmann (2006), Tolerance and Coercion in Islam: Interfaith Relations in the Muslim Tradition, Cambridge University Press, {{ISBN|978-0521026994}}, pp. 42-43</ref> According to [[Fatawa-e-Alamgiri]], a 17th-century compilation of Hanafi fiqh in South Asia, a master who kills his slave should not face capital punishment under the retaliation doctrine.<ref name=scs1>SC Sircar, {{Google books|BUgOAAAAQAAJ|The Muhammadan Law|page=276}}, pp. 276-278</ref>\n\nNon-Hanafi jurists have historically ruled that Qisas does not apply against a Muslim, if he murders any non-Muslim (including dhimmi) or a slave for any reason.<ref name=\"rppb2\"/><ref name=\"J. Norman D. Anderson 2007 pp. 372-373\"/> Both Shafi'i and Maliki fiqh doctrines maintained, notes Friedmann, that the Qisas only applies when there is \"the element of equality between the perpetrator and the victim\"; Qisas is not available to an [[infidel]] victim when the crime's perpetrator is a Muslim because \"equality does not exist between a Muslim and an infidel, and Muslims are exalted above the infidels\".<ref>Yohanan Friedmann (2006), Tolerance and Coercion in Islam: Interfaith Relations in the Muslim Tradition, Cambridge University Press, {{ISBN|978-0521026994}}, pp. 45-46, Quote: \"(...) maintained that the element of equality which is inherent in the concept of qisas \"does not exist between a Muslim and an infidel because infidelity lowered his standing and diminished his rank\" (wa la musawat bayna al-muslim wa al-kafir fa-inna al-kufr hatta manzilatahu wa wada'a martabatahu). Perceiving Muslims as exalted above the infidels is, again, the conceptual basis for determining the law.\"</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Hanbali]] legal school, if a Muslim kills or harms a non-Muslim, even if intentionally, ''Qisas'' does not apply,<ref name=rppb2/> and the sharia court may only impose a [[Diyya]] (monetary compensation) with or without a prison term on the Muslim at its discretion. The [[Maliki]] fiqh also forbids applying ''Qisas'' against a Muslim if the victim is a dhimmi, but has ruled that the Muslim may be killed if the murder was treacherous.<ref name=mkhl1/><ref name=yf1/> If the killing, bodily or property damage was unintentional, the compensation to a non-Muslim was declared to be half of what would be due for an equivalent damage to a Muslim. The [[Shafi'i]] fiqh was similar to Hanbali fiqh, and Qisas did not apply if the victim was a non-Muslim;<ref name=amnhmk/> additionally, Shafi'i jurists held that the compensation for the victim's heirs should be a third of what would be due in case the victim was a Muslim.<ref name=mkhl1/><ref name=rt1/> According to Hanafi school, neither Qisas nor Diyya applied against a Muslim or a dhimmi who killed a Musta'min (foreigner visiting) who did not enjoy permanent protection in [[Divisions of the world in Islam#Dar al-Islam|Dar al-Islam]] and may take up arms against Muslims after returning to his homeland (dar al-harb).<ref>Yohanan Friedmann (2006), Tolerance and Coercion in Islam: Interfaith Relations in the Muslim Tradition, Cambridge University Press, {{ISBN|978-0521026994}}, pp. 42-51</ref>\n\nNeither Qisas nor any other form of compensation applied in case the victim was an [[Apostasy in Islam|apostate]] (converted from Islam to another religion), a person who has committed the [[hudud|hadd]] crime of transgression against Islam or Imam (''baghy''), or a non-Muslim who did not accept himself or herself as a [[Dhimmi]], or if the non-Muslim victim's family could not prove that the victim had paid [[Jizya]] regularly.<ref name=yf1>Yohanan Friedmann (2006), Tolerance and Coercion in Islam: Interfaith Relations in the Muslim Tradition, Cambridge University Press, {{ISBN|978-0521026994}}, pp. 42-50</ref><ref name=rt1>Richard Terrill (2012), World Criminal Justice Systems: A Comparative Survey, Routledge, {{ISBN|978-1455725892}}, pp. 554-562</ref>\n\nMuslim jurists justified the discriminatory application of ''Qisas'' between Muslims and non-Muslims by referring to the following hadith.<ref name=ame2>Anver M. Emon (2012), Religious Pluralism and Islamic Law: Dhimmis and Others in the Empire of Law, Oxford University Press, {{ISBN|978-0199661633}}, pp. 237-250</ref>\n\n{{quotation|Narrated Abdullah ibn Amr ibn al-'As: The Prophet said: A believer will not be killed for an infidel. If anyone kills a man deliberately, he is to be handed over to the relatives of the one who has been killed. If they wish, they may kill, but if they wish, they may accept [[Diyya|blood-wit]].|{{hadith-usc|usc=yes|Abudawud|39|4491}}}}\n\nNumerous Hanafi, Shafi'i and Maliki jurists stated that a Muslim and a non-Muslim are neither equal nor of same status under sharia, and thus the judicial process and punishment applicable must vary.<ref name=ame2/>\n\n==Current practice==\n\n''Qi\u1e63\u0101\u1e63'' is currently provided for by legal systems of several countries which apply traditional Islamic jurisprudence (Saudi Arabia) or have enacted qisas laws as part of modern legal reforms.\n\n===Iran===\nThrough sections 1 through 80 of [[Iran]]'s penal code, Qisas have been enacted as one of the methods of punishment.<ref>[http://www.nyulawglobal.org/globalex/Iran.htm A Guide to the Legal System of the Islamic Republic of Iran] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120107082546/http://www.nyulawglobal.org/globalex/Iran.htm |date=January 7, 2012 }}, March 2006</ref><ref>[http://www.iran-law.com/IMG/pdf/Iran_Criminal_Code_in_English.pdf Islamic Penal Code of the Islamic Republic of Iran] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327092745/http://www.iran-law.com/IMG/pdf/Iran_Criminal_Code_in_English.pdf |date=2014-03-27 }}, Book 3</ref> Iran penal code outlines two types of Qisas crime - Qisas for life, and Qisas for part of human body.<ref name=smshah>Shahid M. Shahidullah, Comparative Criminal Justice Systems: Global and Local Perspectives, {{ISBN|978-1-4496-0425-7}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=eZD-MHVMHsQC&pg=PA425 pp. 425]-426</ref> In cases of qisas for life, the victim's family may with the permission of court, take the life of the murderer. In cases of qisas for part of human body, section 55 of Iran's penal code grants the victim or victim's family to, with permission of the court, inflict an equal injury to the perpetrator's body. If the victim lost the right hand and perpetrator does not have a right hand for qisas, then with court's permission, the victim may cut the left hand of the perpetrator.<ref name=smshah/>\n\nIn one episode, ''qi\u1e63\u0101\u1e63'' was demanded by [[Ameneh Bahrami]], an Iranian woman blinded in an acid attack. She demanded that her attacker Majiv Movahedi be blinded as well.<ref>\"In Iran, a case of an eye for an eye\" ''Phillie Metro'' March 29, 2009</ref>  In 2011, Bahrami retracted her demand on the day the sentence was to be carried out, requesting instead that her attacker be pardoned.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-14356886 \"Iranian sentenced to be blinded for acid attack is pardoned\" (BBC News, 31 July 2011)]</ref>\n\nA prisoner lodged in the [[Gohardasht Prison]] of the city of [[Karaj]], was reported to have been blinded in March 2015 after being convicted for an acid attack on another man in 2009 and sentenced to the punishment under \"qisas\".<ref>{{cite web| first= Andrew | last= Marszal | url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/iran/11455200/Iran-condemned-for-unspeakably-cruel-blinding-of-prisoner.html | title= Iran condemned for 'unspeakably cruel' blinding of prisoner | website = Telegraph |date = 6 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Pakistan===\n{{See also|Islamization in Pakistan}}\n[[Pakistan]] introduced Qisas and [[Diyya|Diyat]] in 1990 as ''Criminal Law (Second Amendment) Ordinance'', after the Shariat Appellate Bench of the [[Supreme Court of Pakistan]] declared that the lack of Qisas and Diyat were repugnant to the injunctions of Islam as laid down by the Quran and Sunnah.<ref>''Federation of Pakistan v. Gul Hasan Khan'', PLD 1989 [[Supreme Court of Pakistan|SC]] 633\u2013685, affirming PLD 1980 [[Peshawar High Court|Pesh]] 1\u201320 and PLD 1980 [[Federal Shariat Court|FSC]] 1\u201360</ref> Pakistani parliament enacted the law of Qisas and Diyat as ''Criminal Law (Amendment) Act, 1997''.<ref>see [[Pakistan Penal Code|PPC]] [http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/legislation/1860/actXLVof1860.html#f111 ss. 299\u2013338-H]; Tahir Wasti (2009), The Application of Islamic Criminal Law in Pakistan: Sharia in Practice, {{ISBN|978-90-04-17225-8}}, Brill, [https://books.google.com/books?hl=de&id=88-XutlkJAQC&pg=PA8 p. 8]</ref> An offender may still be punished despite pardoning by way of [[Tazir|ta'z\u012br]] or if not all the persons entitled to Qisas joined in the compromise.<ref>[[Pakistan Penal Code]] s. 311; ''Azmat and another v. The State'', PLD 2009 [[Supreme Court of Pakistan]] 768</ref> The Pakistan Penal Code modernized the [[Hanafi]] doctrine of ''qisas'' and ''diya'' by eliminating distinctions between Muslims and non-Muslims.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Application of Islamic Criminal Law in Pakistan|author=Tahir Wasti|publisher=Brill|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=88-XutlkJAQC&pg=PA49|page=49|year=2009}}</ref>\n\n===Nigeria===\nSince the 1960s, several northern states of Nigeria have enacted sharia-based criminal laws, including provisions for Qisas. These codes have been applied in the Sharia Courts of Nigeria to Muslims. Many have been sentenced to retaliation under the Qisas principle, as well as to other punishments such as hudud and tazir.<ref>G.J. Weimann (2007), \"Judicial Practice in Islamic Criminal Law in Nigeria 2000 to 2004\u2014A Tentative Overview,\" Islamic Law & Society, 14(2), pp. 240\u2013286</ref><ref>I.K. Oraegbunam (2012), Penal Jurisprudence under Islamic Criminal Justice: Implications for the Right to Human Dignity in Nigerian Constitution, Journal Islamic State Practices in Int'l Law, 8, pp. 31-49</ref>\n\n===Saudi Arabia===\nMurder and manslaughter are private offenses in Saudi Arabia, which a victim or victim's heirs must prosecute, or accept monetary compensation, or grant pardon.<ref name=hrwsa1/> The sharia courts in Saudi Arabia apply Qisas to juvenile cases, with previous limit of 7 year raised to 12 year age limit, for both boys or girls.<ref>Child Rights International Network (March 2013), [http://www.crin.org/en/library/publications/saudi-arabia-inhuman-sentencing-children Inhuman sentencing of children in Saudi Arabia], 17th session of the Human Rights Council Universal Periodic Review; Don Cipriani (2009), Children\u2019s Rights and the Minimum Age of Criminal Responsibility, Farnham: Ashgate Publishing, {{ISBN|978-0754677307}}</ref> This age limit is not effectively enforced, and the court can assess a child defendant's physical characteristics to decide if he or she should be tried as an adult. In most cases, a person who satisfies at least one of the following four characteristics is considered as an adult for Qisas cases:<ref name=hrwsa1/> (1) above the age of 15, (2) has wet dreams (''al-ihtilam''), (3) any appearance of pubic hair, or (4) start of menstruation. Qisas principle, when enforced in Saudi Arabia, means equal retaliation and damage on the defendant.<ref name=hrwsa1>Human Rights Watch (2008), The Last Holdouts, Juvenile Death Penalty in Iran, Saudi Arabia, Sudan, Pakistan and Yemen, {{ISBN|1564323757}}, pp. 7-9; [https://www.hrw.org/reports/2008/crd0908/2.htm Archived summary]</ref>\n\nAccording to reports in Saudi media, in 2013, a court in Saudi Arabia sentenced a defendant to have his spinal cord severed to paralyze him, unless he paid one million Saudi riyals (about US$270,000) in Diyya compensation to the victim. The offender allegedly stabbed his friend in the back, rendering him paralysed from the waist down in or around 2003.<ref name=IBT>{{cite news|last1=Nair|first1=Drishya|title=saudi arabia: man who paralyzed friend to have spinal cord severed|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/saudi-arabia-punishments-stab-paralise-spinal-cord-452683|accessdate=16 February 2015|agency=International Business Times|date=April 2, 2013}}</ref> Other reported sentences of qisas in KSA have included eye gouging, tooth extraction, and death in cases of murder.<ref>[https://www.amnesty.org/en/news/saudi-arabia-news-paralysis-sentence-outrageous-2013-04-02 Saudi Arabia: News of paralysis sentence \"outrageous\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217153237/http://www.amnesty.org/en/news/saudi-arabia-news-paralysis-sentence-outrageous-2013-04-02 |date=February 17, 2015 }} Amnesty International (2 April 2013)</ref>\n\n==Qisas and honor crimes==\nAccording to most variations of Sharia, neither Qisas nor [[Tazir]] applies if a Muslim parent or grandparent kills their child<ref name=scs1/> or grandchild,<ref name=shlw1/> or if the murder victim is a spouse with whom one has surviving children.<ref name=shlw1/> The culprit can be, however, subject to Diyya (financial compensation) which is payable to the surviving heirs of the victims.<ref name=shlw1>Sara Hossain and Lynn Welchman (2005), 'Honour': Crimes, Paradigms and Violence Against Women, {{ISBN|978-1842776278}}, pp. 85-86</ref>\n\nThe four major schools of Sunni Sharia have been divided on applicability of Qisas when the victim is a child, and the father is the murderer. The Hanafi, Shafi'i and Hanbali Sunni sharias have ruled that Qisas does not apply, as has the Shia Sharia doctrine. The Maliki school, however, has ruled that Qisas may be demanded by the mother if a father kills his son.<ref name=\"mohelawa\"/><ref>Tahir Wasti (2009), The Application of Islamic Criminal Law in Pakistan: Sharia in Practice, Brill, {{ISBN|978-9004172258}}, p. 90</ref> The Hanafi, Hanbali and Shafi'i sharia extend this principle to cases when the victim is a child and the mother or grandparents are the murderers.<ref name=amnhmk>Al-Misri (Translated by Nuh Ha Mim Keller), [[Reliance of the Traveller]], {{ISBN|978-0915957729}}, Ruling O:1.2, Quote: \"The following are not subject to retaliation: (2) a Muslim for killing a non-Muslim; (4) a father or mother (or their fathers or mothers) for killing their offpsring, or offspring's offpsring; (5) nor is retaliation permissible to a descendant such as when his father kills his mother\"</ref><ref>Tahir Wasti (2009), The Application of Islamic Criminal Law in Pakistan: Sharia in Practice, Brill, {{ISBN|978-9004172258}}</ref>\n\nScholars suggest that this exemption of parents and relatives from Qisas, and the treatment of homicide-related Qisas as a civil dispute that should be handled privately by victim's family under sharia doctrine, encourages [[honor crime]]s, particularly against females, as well as allows the murderer(s) to go unpunished.<ref>Stephanie Palo (2008), A Charade of Change: Qisas and Diyat Ordinance Allows Honor Killings to Go Unpunished in Pakistan, UC Davis Journal Int'l Law & Policy, 15, pp. 93-99</ref><ref>RA Ruane (2000), Murder in the Name of Honor: Violence Against Women in Jordan and Pakistan. Emory Int'l Law Review, 14, pp. 1523-1532</ref><ref name=hanirf1>Hannah Irfan (2008), Honor Related Violence Against Women in Pakistan, World Justice Forum, Vienna July 2\u20135, pp. 9-12</ref> This, state Devers and Bacon, is why many honor crimes are not reported to the police, nor handled in the public arena.<ref>Lindsey Devers and Sarah Bacon (2010), [http://pi.library.yorku.ca/ojs/index.php/ijcst/article/viewFile/25925/24007 Interpreting Honor Crimes: The Institutional Disregard Towards Female Victims of Family Violence in the Middle East], International Journal of Criminology and Sociological Theory, Vol. 3, No. 1, June 2010, pp. 359-371</ref><ref>Sharbanoo Keshavarz (2006), Honor Killing in Iran: a Legal Point of View, Yearbook of Islamic & Middle East Law (2006-2007), Vol 13, pp. 87-103</ref> Historically, Sharia did not stipulate any punishment against the accused when the victim is the child or the spouse of the murderer, but in modern times some Sharia-based Muslim countries have introduced laws that grant courts the discretion to impose imprisonment of the murderer.<ref name=shlw1/> However, the victim's heirs have the right to waive Qisas, seek Diyat, or pardon the killer.<ref name=hanirf1/><ref name=sms1>Shahid M. Shahidullah (2012), Comparative Criminal Justice Systems: Global and Local Perspectives, {{ISBN|978-1449604257}}, pp. 511</ref>\n\n==''Eye for an eye''==\nA legal concept similar to Qisas is the principle of ''[[Eye for an eye]]'' first recorded in the [[Code of Hammurabi]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Sharia]]\n* [[Hudud]]\n* [[Tazir]]\n* [[Diyya]]\n* [[Application of sharia law by country]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Arabic words and phrases in Sharia]]\n[[Category:Islamic terminology]]\n[[Category:Islamic criminal jurisprudence]]\n[[Category:Punishments in religion]]\n[[Category:Islam and violence]]\n[[Category:Islam and capital punishment]]\n[[Category:Sharia legal terminology]]\n", "text_old": "{{hatnote |This is a sub-article of [[Islamic criminal jurisprudence]].}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{Fiqh |criminal}}\n'''Qi\u1e63\u0101\u1e63''' ({{lang-ar|{{large|\u0642\u0635\u0627\u0635}}}}) is an [[Islamic term]] meaning \"retaliation in kind\",<ref name=mohelawa>Mohamed S. El-Awa (1993), Punishment In Islamic Law, American Trust Publications, {{ISBN|978-0892591428}}</ref><ref>Shahid M. Shahidullah, Comparative Criminal Justice Systems: Global and Local Perspectives, {{ISBN|978-1449604257}}, pp. 370-372</ref> \"[[eye for an eye]]\", or retributive justice. In traditional Islamic law (''[[sharia]]''), the doctrine of qisas provides for a punishment analogous to the crime. Qisas is available to the victim or victim's heirs against a convicted perpetrator of murder or intentional bodily injury.<ref>Tahir Wasti (2009), The Application of Islamic Criminal Law in Pakistan: Sharia in Practice, Brill Academic, {{ISBN|978-9004172258}}, pp. 12-13</ref> In the case of murder, qisas gives the right to take the life of the killer, if the latter is convicted and the court approves.<ref>Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, [http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/485784/qisas Qisas] (2012)</ref> Those who are entitled to ''qisas'' have the option of receiving monetary compensation (''[[diyya]]'') or granting pardon to the perpetrator instead.\n\nQisas is one of several forms of punishment in traditional [[Islamic criminal jurisprudence]], the others being [[Hudud]] and [[Tazir|Ta'zir]].<ref>Asghar Schirazi (1997), The Constitution of Iran : politics and the state in the Islamic Republic, I.B. Tauris London, pp. 222-225</ref> The legal systems of Iran, Pakistan, Saudi Arabia and some Nigerian states currently provide for qisas.\n\n==Islamic scriptures==\n\n=== Quran ===\nThe Qisas or equivalence verse in [[Quran]] is,<ref name=mohelawa/>\n\n{{quotation|O ye who believe! the law of equality is prescribed to you in cases of murder: the free for the free, the slave for the slave, the woman for the woman. But if any remission is made by the brother of the slain, then grant any reasonable demand, and compensate him with handsome gratitude, this is a concession and a Mercy from your Lord. After this whoever exceeds the limits shall be in grave penalty.|{{cite quran|2|178|style=nosup}}}}\n\nThe [[Qur'an]] allows the aggrieved party to receive monetary compensation (blood money, ''[[diyya]]'', {{large|\u062f\u064a\u0629}}) instead of qisas,<ref>Christie S. Warren, Islamic Criminal Law, Oxford University Press, [http://www.oxfordbibliographies.com/view/document/obo-9780195390155/obo-9780195390155-0035.xml?rskey=3wT5QM&result=1&q=qisas#firstMatch Qisas]</ref> or forfeit the right of ''qi\u1e63\u0101\u1e63'' as an act of charity or in atonement for the victim family's past sins.\n\n{{quotation|We ordained therein for them: \"Life for life, [[eye for an eye|eye for eye]], nose for nose, ear for ear, tooth for tooth, and wounds equal for equal.\" But if any one remits the retaliation by way of charity, it is an act of atonement for himself. And if any fail to judge by (the light of) what Allah hath revealed, they are (No better than) wrong-doers.|{{cite quran|5|45|style=nosup}}}}\n\n=== Hadith ===\n\nThe [[Hadith]]s have extensive discussion of qisas. For example, Sahih Bukhari states,\n\n{{quotation|Allah's Apostle said, \"The blood of a Muslim who confesses that none has the right to be worshipped but Allah and that I am His Apostle, cannot be shed except in three cases: ''In Qisas for murder'', a married person who commits illegal sexual intercourse and the one who reverts from Islam (apostate) and leaves the Muslims.\"|{{Hadith-usc|usc=yes|bukhari|9|83|17}}}}\n\n{{quotation|Narrated Anas: The daughter of An-Nadr slapped a girl and broke her incisor tooth. They (the relatives of that girl), came to the Prophet and he gave the order of Qisas (equality in punishment).|{{Hadith-usc|usc=yes|bukhari|9|83|32}} }}\n\nMany premodern Islamic scholars ruled that only ''diya'' (blood money) and not ''qisas'' was available when the victim was a non-Muslim [[dhimmi]] and to non-Muslim slaves owned by a Muslim, based on hadith.<ref>Anver M. Emon (2012), Religious Pluralism and Islamic Law: Dhimmis and Others in the Empire of Law, Oxford University Press, {{ISBN|978-0199661633}}, pp. 237-249; Quote \"Muslim jurists defended this discriminatory application of qisas liability by reference to a hadith in which the Prophet said: 'A believer is not killed for an unbeliever or one without a covenant during his residency.' Jurists who constructed discriminatory rules of liability relied on the first half of the hadith. Furthermore, they argued that these discriminatory rules reflected the fact that Muslims were of a higher class than their non-Muslim co-residents.\"; Quote 2 \"Furthermore, using the logical inference of a minore ad maius, [[Al-Mawardi]] held that just as a Muslim bears no liability for sexually slandering a [[dhimmi]], he cannot be liable for killing one, a much more serious offense.</ref>\n\n{{quotation|Narrated Abu Juhaifa: I asked 'Ali \"Do you have anything Divine literature besides what is in the Qur'an?\" Or, as Uyaina once said, \"Apart from what the people have?\" 'Ali said, \"By Him Who made the grain split (germinate) and created the soul, we have nothing except what is in the Quran and the ability (gift) of understanding Allah's Book which He may endow a man, with and what is written in this sheet of paper.\" I asked, \"What is on this paper?\" He replied, \"The legal regulations of Diya (Blood-money) and the (ransom for) releasing of the captives, and the judgment that ''no Muslim should be killed in Qisas (equality in punishment) for killing a Kafir (disbeliever)''.\"|{{Hadith-usc|usc=yes|bukhari|9|83|50}} see also {{Hadith-usc|usc=yes|bukhari|1|3|111}} {{Hadith-usc|usc=no|bukhari|4|52|283}} {{hadith-usc|usc=yes|Abudawud|39|4515}} }}\n\n==Traditional jurisprudence==\n{{Undue weight|Section|date=April 2019}}\n\nTraditional Islamic jurisprudence (''[[fiqh]]'') treats homicide as a civil dispute,<ref>Tahir Wasti (2009), The Application of Islamic Criminal Law in Pakistan: Sharia in Practice, Brill Academic, {{ISBN|978-9004172258}}, pp. 283-288</ref> rather than an act requiring corrective punishment by the state to maintain order.<ref name=\"guardian 2014\">{{cite news|last1=Malik|first1=Nesrine|title=Paralysis or blood money? Skewed justice in Saudi Arabia|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/apr/05/sharia-law-diyya-saudi|accessdate=14 February 2015|agency=The Guardian|date=5 April 2013}}</ref> In all cases of murder, unintentional homicide, bodily injury and property damage, under traditional Islamic law, the prosecutor is not the state, but only the victim or the victim's heir (or owner, in the case when the victim is a slave). Qisas can only be demanded by the victim or victim's heirs.<ref>Rudolph Peters (2006), Crime and Punishment in Islamic Law, Cambridge University Press, {{ISBN|978-0521796705}}, pp. 44-49, 114, 186-187</ref>\n\nAccording to classical jurists of the [[Shafi'i]], [[Maliki]] and [[Hanbali]] schools, ''qisas'' is available only when the victim is Muslim, while the [[Hanafi]] school took a different stance on this point.<ref name=mkhl1>Majid Khadduri and Herbert J. Liebesny, Law in the Middle East: Origin and Development of Islamic Law, 2nd Edition, Lawbook Exchange, {{ISBN|978-1584778646}}, pp. 337-345</ref><ref name=rppb2>Rudolph Peters and Peri Bearman (2014), The Ashgate Research Companion to Islamic Law, {{ISBN|978-1409438939}}, pp. 169-170</ref><ref name=\"J. Norman D. Anderson 2007 pp. 372-373\">J. Norman D. Anderson (2007), Islamic Law in Africa, Routledge, {{ISBN|978-0415611862}}, pp. 372-373</ref>\n\nIn the early history of Islam, there were considerable disagreements in Muslim jurist opinions on applicability of Qisas and Diyya when a Muslim murdered a non-Muslim ([[Dhimmi]], [[Musta'min]] or slave).<ref name=yf1/><ref>Tahir Wasti (2009), The Application of Islamic Criminal Law in Pakistan: Sharia in Practice, Brill, {{ISBN|978-9004172258}}, pp. 89-90</ref> Most scholars of [[Hanafi]] school of fiqh ruled that, if a Muslim killed a dhimmi or a slave, Qisas (retaliation) was applicable against the Muslim, but this could be averted by paying a Diyya.<ref name=yf1/><ref name=rppb1>Rudolph Peters and Peri Bearman (2014), The Ashgate Research Companion to Islamic Law, {{ISBN|978-1409438939}}, pp. 129-137</ref> In one case, the Hanafi jurist [[Abu Yusuf]] initially ordered Qisas when a Muslim killed a dhimmi, but under Caliph [[Harun al-Rashid]]'s pressure replaced the order with Diyya if the victim's family members were unable to prove the victim was paying [[jizya]] willingly as a dhimmi.<ref>Yohanan Friedmann (2006), Tolerance and Coercion in Islam: Interfaith Relations in the Muslim Tradition, Cambridge University Press, {{ISBN|978-0521026994}}, pp. 42-43</ref> According to [[Fatawa-e-Alamgiri]], a 17th-century compilation of Hanafi fiqh in South Asia, a master who kills his slave should not face capital punishment under the retaliation doctrine.<ref name=scs1>SC Sircar, {{Google books|BUgOAAAAQAAJ|The Muhammadan Law|page=276}}, pp. 276-278</ref>\n\nNon-Hanafi jurists have historically ruled that Qisas does not apply against a Muslim, if he murders any non-Muslim (including dhimmi) or a slave for any reason.<ref name=\"rppb2\"/><ref name=\"J. Norman D. Anderson 2007 pp. 372-373\"/> Both Shafi'i and Maliki fiqh doctrines maintained, notes Friedmann, that the Qisas only applies when there is \"the element of equality between the perpetrator and the victim\"; Qisas is not available to an [[infidel]] victim when the crime's perpetrator is a Muslim because \"equality does not exist between a Muslim and an infidel, and Muslims are exalted above the infidels\".<ref>Yohanan Friedmann (2006), Tolerance and Coercion in Islam: Interfaith Relations in the Muslim Tradition, Cambridge University Press, {{ISBN|978-0521026994}}, pp. 45-46, Quote: \"(...) maintained that the element of equality which is inherent in the concept of qisas \"does not exist between a Muslim and an infidel because infidelity lowered his standing and diminished his rank\" (wa la musawat bayna al-muslim wa al-kafir fa-inna al-kufr hatta manzilatahu wa wada'a martabatahu). Perceiving Muslims as exalted above the infidels is, again, the conceptual basis for determining the law.\"</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Hanbali]] legal school, if a Muslim kills or harms a non-Muslim, even if intentionally, ''Qisas'' does not apply,<ref name=rppb2/> and the sharia court may only impose a [[Diyya]] (monetary compensation) with or without a prison term on the Muslim at its discretion. The [[Maliki]] fiqh also forbids applying ''Qisas'' against a Muslim if the victim is a dhimmi, but has ruled that the Muslim may be killed if the murder was treacherous.<ref name=mkhl1/><ref name=yf1/> If the killing, bodily or property damage was unintentional, the compensation to a non-Muslim was declared to be half of what would be due for an equivalent damage to a Muslim. The [[Shafi'i]] fiqh was similar to Hanbali fiqh, and Qisas did not apply if the victim was a non-Muslim;<ref name=amnhmk/> additionally, Shafi'i jurists held that the compensation for the victim's heirs should be a third of what would be due in case the victim was a Muslim.<ref name=mkhl1/><ref name=rt1/> According to Hanafi school, neither Qisas nor Diyya applied against a Muslim or a dhimmi who killed a Musta'min (foreigner visiting) who did not enjoy permanent protection in [[Divisions of the world in Islam#Dar al-Islam|Dar al-Islam]] and may take up arms against Muslims after returning to his homeland (dar al-harb).<ref>Yohanan Friedmann (2006), Tolerance and Coercion in Islam: Interfaith Relations in the Muslim Tradition, Cambridge University Press, {{ISBN|978-0521026994}}, pp. 42-51</ref>\n\nNeither Qisas nor any other form of compensation applied in case the victim was an [[Apostasy in Islam|apostate]] (converted from Islam to another religion), a person who has committed the [[hudud|hadd]] crime of transgression against Islam or Imam (''baghy''), or a non-Muslim who did not accept himself or herself as a [[Dhimmi]], or if the non-Muslim victim's family could not prove that the victim had paid [[Jizya]] regularly.<ref name=yf1>Yohanan Friedmann (2006), Tolerance and Coercion in Islam: Interfaith Relations in the Muslim Tradition, Cambridge University Press, {{ISBN|978-0521026994}}, pp. 42-50</ref><ref name=rt1>Richard Terrill (2012), World Criminal Justice Systems: A Comparative Survey, Routledge, {{ISBN|978-1455725892}}, pp. 554-562</ref>\n\nMuslim jurists justified the discriminatory application of ''Qisas'' between Muslims and non-Muslims by referring to the following hadith.<ref name=ame2>Anver M. Emon (2012), Religious Pluralism and Islamic Law: Dhimmis and Others in the Empire of Law, Oxford University Press, {{ISBN|978-0199661633}}, pp. 237-250</ref>\n\n{{quotation|Narrated Abdullah ibn Amr ibn al-'As: The Prophet said: A believer will not be killed for an infidel. If anyone kills a man deliberately, he is to be handed over to the relatives of the one who has been killed. If they wish, they may kill, but if they wish, they may accept [[Diyya|blood-wit]].|{{hadith-usc|usc=yes|Abudawud|39|4491}}}}\n\nNumerous Hanafi, Shafi'i and Maliki jurists stated that a Muslim and a non-Muslim are neither equal nor of same status under sharia, and thus the judicial process and punishment applicable must vary.<ref name=ame2/>\n\n==Current practice==\n\n''Qi\u1e63\u0101\u1e63'' is currently provided for by legal systems of several countries which apply traditional Islamic jurisprudence (Saudi Arabia) or have enacted qisas laws as part of modern legal reforms.\n\n===Iran===\nThrough sections 1 through 80 of [[Iran]]'s penal code, Qisas have been enacted as one of the methods of punishment.<ref>[http://www.nyulawglobal.org/globalex/Iran.htm A Guide to the Legal System of the Islamic Republic of Iran] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120107082546/http://www.nyulawglobal.org/globalex/Iran.htm |date=January 7, 2012 }}, March 2006</ref><ref>[http://www.iran-law.com/IMG/pdf/Iran_Criminal_Code_in_English.pdf Islamic Penal Code of the Islamic Republic of Iran] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327092745/http://www.iran-law.com/IMG/pdf/Iran_Criminal_Code_in_English.pdf |date=2014-03-27 }}, Book 3</ref> Iran penal code outlines two types of Qisas crime - Qisas for life, and Qisas for part of human body.<ref name=smshah>Shahid M. Shahidullah, Comparative Criminal Justice Systems: Global and Local Perspectives, {{ISBN|978-1-4496-0425-7}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=eZD-MHVMHsQC&pg=PA425 pp. 425]-426</ref> In cases of qisas for life, the victim's family may with the permission of court, take the life of the murderer. In cases of qisas for part of human body, section 55 of Iran's penal code grants the victim or victim's family to, with permission of the court, inflict an equal injury to the perpetrator's body. If the victim lost the right hand and perpetrator does not have a right hand for qisas, then with court's permission, the victim may cut the left hand of the perpetrator.<ref name=smshah/>\n\nIn one episode, ''qi\u1e63\u0101\u1e63'' was demanded by [[Ameneh Bahrami]], an Iranian woman blinded in an acid attack. She demanded that her attacker Majiv Movahedi be blinded as well.<ref>\"In Iran, a case of an eye for an eye\" ''Phillie Metro'' March 29, 2009</ref>  In 2011, Bahrami retracted her demand on the day the sentence was to be carried out, requesting instead that her attacker be pardoned.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-14356886 \"Iranian sentenced to be blinded for acid attack is pardoned\" (BBC News, 31 July 2011)]</ref>\n\nA prisoner lodged in the [[Gohardasht Prison]] of the city of [[Karaj]], was reported to have been blinded in March 2015 after being convicted for an acid attack on another man in 2009 and sentenced to the punishment under \"qisas\".<ref>{{cite web| first= Andrew | last= Marszal | url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/iran/11455200/Iran-condemned-for-unspeakably-cruel-blinding-of-prisoner.html | title= Iran condemned for 'unspeakably cruel' blinding of prisoner | website = Telegraph |date = 6 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Pakistan===\n[[Pakistan]] introduced Qisas and [[Diyya|Diyat]] in 1990 as ''Criminal Law (Second Amendment) Ordinance'', after the Shariat Appellate Bench of the [[Supreme Court of Pakistan]] declared that the lack of Qisas and Diyat were repugnant to the injunctions of Islam as laid down by the Quran and Sunnah.<ref>''Federation of Pakistan v. Gul Hasan Khan'', PLD 1989 [[Supreme Court of Pakistan|SC]] 633\u2013685, affirming PLD 1980 [[Peshawar High Court|Pesh]] 1\u201320 and PLD 1980 [[Federal Shariat Court|FSC]] 1\u201360</ref> Pakistani parliament enacted the law of Qisas and Diyat as ''Criminal Law (Amendment) Act, 1997''.<ref>see [[Pakistan Penal Code|PPC]] [http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/legislation/1860/actXLVof1860.html#f111 ss. 299\u2013338-H]; Tahir Wasti (2009), The Application of Islamic Criminal Law in Pakistan: Sharia in Practice, {{ISBN|978-90-04-17225-8}}, Brill, [https://books.google.com/books?hl=de&id=88-XutlkJAQC&pg=PA8 p. 8]</ref> An offender may still be punished despite pardoning by way of [[Tazir|ta'z\u012br]] or if not all the persons entitled to Qisas joined in the compromise.<ref>[[Pakistan Penal Code]] s. 311; ''Azmat and another v. The State'', PLD 2009 [[Supreme Court of Pakistan]] 768</ref> The Pakistan Penal Code modernized the Hanafi doctrine of ''qisas'' and ''diya'' by eliminating distinctions between Muslims and non-Muslims.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Application of Islamic Criminal Law in Pakistan|author=Tahir Wasti|publisher=Brill|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=88-XutlkJAQC&pg=PA49|page=49|year=2009}}</ref>\n\n===Nigeria===\nSince the 1960s, several northern states of Nigeria have enacted sharia-based criminal laws, including provisions for Qisas. These codes have been applied in the Sharia Courts of Nigeria to Muslims. Many have been sentenced to retaliation under the Qisas principle, as well as to other punishments such as hudud and tazir.<ref>G.J. Weimann (2007), \"Judicial Practice in Islamic Criminal Law in Nigeria 2000 to 2004\u2014A Tentative Overview,\" Islamic Law & Society, 14(2), pp. 240\u2013286</ref><ref>I.K. Oraegbunam (2012), Penal Jurisprudence under Islamic Criminal Justice: Implications for the Right to Human Dignity in Nigerian Constitution, Journal Islamic State Practices in Int'l Law, 8, pp. 31-49</ref>\n\n===Saudi Arabia===\nMurder and manslaughter are private offenses in Saudi Arabia, which a victim or victim's heirs must prosecute, or accept monetary compensation, or grant pardon.<ref name=hrwsa1/> The sharia courts in Saudi Arabia apply Qisas to juvenile cases, with previous limit of 7 year raised to 12 year age limit, for both boys or girls.<ref>Child Rights International Network (March 2013), [http://www.crin.org/en/library/publications/saudi-arabia-inhuman-sentencing-children Inhuman sentencing of children in Saudi Arabia], 17th session of the Human Rights Council Universal Periodic Review; Don Cipriani (2009), Children\u2019s Rights and the Minimum Age of Criminal Responsibility, Farnham: Ashgate Publishing, {{ISBN|978-0754677307}}</ref> This age limit is not effectively enforced, and the court can assess a child defendant's physical characteristics to decide if he or she should be tried as an adult. In most cases, a person who satisfies at least one of the following four characteristics is considered as an adult for Qisas cases:<ref name=hrwsa1/> (1) above the age of 15, (2) has wet dreams (''al-ihtilam''), (3) any appearance of pubic hair, or (4) start of menstruation. Qisas principle, when enforced in Saudi Arabia, means equal retaliation and damage on the defendant.<ref name=hrwsa1>Human Rights Watch (2008), The Last Holdouts, Juvenile Death Penalty in Iran, Saudi Arabia, Sudan, Pakistan and Yemen, {{ISBN|1564323757}}, pp. 7-9; [https://www.hrw.org/reports/2008/crd0908/2.htm Archived summary]</ref>\n\nAccording to reports in Saudi media, in 2013, a court in Saudi Arabia sentenced a defendant to have his spinal cord severed to paralyze him, unless he paid one million Saudi riyals (about US$270,000) in Diyya compensation to the victim. The offender allegedly stabbed his friend in the back, rendering him paralysed from the waist down in or around 2003.<ref name=IBT>{{cite news|last1=Nair|first1=Drishya|title=saudi arabia: man who paralyzed friend to have spinal cord severed|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/saudi-arabia-punishments-stab-paralise-spinal-cord-452683|accessdate=16 February 2015|agency=International Business Times|date=April 2, 2013}}</ref> Other reported sentences of qisas in KSA have included eye gouging, tooth extraction, and death in cases of murder.<ref>[https://www.amnesty.org/en/news/saudi-arabia-news-paralysis-sentence-outrageous-2013-04-02 Saudi Arabia: News of paralysis sentence \"outrageous\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217153237/http://www.amnesty.org/en/news/saudi-arabia-news-paralysis-sentence-outrageous-2013-04-02 |date=February 17, 2015 }} Amnesty International (2 April 2013)</ref>\n\n==Qisas and honor crimes==\nAccording to most variations of Sharia, neither Qisas nor [[Tazir]] applies if a Muslim parent or grandparent kills their child<ref name=scs1/> or grandchild,<ref name=shlw1/> or if the murder victim is a spouse with whom one has surviving children.<ref name=shlw1/> The culprit can be, however, subject to Diyya (financial compensation) which is payable to the surviving heirs of the victims.<ref name=shlw1>Sara Hossain and Lynn Welchman (2005), 'Honour': Crimes, Paradigms and Violence Against Women, {{ISBN|978-1842776278}}, pp. 85-86</ref>\n\nThe four major schools of Sunni Sharia have been divided on applicability of Qisas when the victim is a child, and the father is the murderer. The Hanafi, Shafi'i and Hanbali Sunni sharias have ruled that Qisas does not apply, as has the Shia Sharia doctrine. The Maliki school, however, has ruled that Qisas may be demanded by the mother if a father kills his son.<ref name=\"mohelawa\"/><ref>Tahir Wasti (2009), The Application of Islamic Criminal Law in Pakistan: Sharia in Practice, Brill, {{ISBN|978-9004172258}}, p. 90</ref> The Hanafi, Hanbali and Shafi'i sharia extend this principle to cases when the victim is a child and the mother or grandparents are the murderers.<ref name=amnhmk>Al-Misri (Translated by Nuh Ha Mim Keller), [[Reliance of the Traveller]], {{ISBN|978-0915957729}}, Ruling O:1.2, Quote: \"The following are not subject to retaliation: (2) a Muslim for killing a non-Muslim; (4) a father or mother (or their fathers or mothers) for killing their offpsring, or offspring's offpsring; (5) nor is retaliation permissible to a descendant such as when his father kills his mother\"</ref><ref>Tahir Wasti (2009), The Application of Islamic Criminal Law in Pakistan: Sharia in Practice, Brill, {{ISBN|978-9004172258}}</ref>\n\nScholars suggest that this exemption of parents and relatives from Qisas, and the treatment of homicide-related Qisas as a civil dispute that should be handled privately by victim's family under sharia doctrine, encourages [[honor crime]]s, particularly against females, as well as allows the murderer(s) to go unpunished.<ref>Stephanie Palo (2008), A Charade of Change: Qisas and Diyat Ordinance Allows Honor Killings to Go Unpunished in Pakistan, UC Davis Journal Int'l Law & Policy, 15, pp. 93-99</ref><ref>RA Ruane (2000), Murder in the Name of Honor: Violence Against Women in Jordan and Pakistan. Emory Int'l Law Review, 14, pp. 1523-1532</ref><ref name=hanirf1>Hannah Irfan (2008), Honor Related Violence Against Women in Pakistan, World Justice Forum, Vienna July 2\u20135, pp. 9-12</ref> This, state Devers and Bacon, is why many honor crimes are not reported to the police, nor handled in the public arena.<ref>Lindsey Devers and Sarah Bacon (2010), [http://pi.library.yorku.ca/ojs/index.php/ijcst/article/viewFile/25925/24007 Interpreting Honor Crimes: The Institutional Disregard Towards Female Victims of Family Violence in the Middle East], International Journal of Criminology and Sociological Theory, Vol. 3, No. 1, June 2010, pp. 359-371</ref><ref>Sharbanoo Keshavarz (2006), Honor Killing in Iran: a Legal Point of View, Yearbook of Islamic & Middle East Law (2006-2007), Vol 13, pp. 87-103</ref> Historically, Sharia did not stipulate any punishment against the accused when the victim is the child or the spouse of the murderer, but in modern times some Sharia-based Muslim countries have introduced laws that grant courts the discretion to impose imprisonment of the murderer.<ref name=shlw1/> However, the victim's heirs have the right to waive Qisas, seek Diyat, or pardon the killer.<ref name=hanirf1/><ref name=sms1>Shahid M. Shahidullah (2012), Comparative Criminal Justice Systems: Global and Local Perspectives, {{ISBN|978-1449604257}}, pp. 511</ref>\n\n==''Eye for an eye''==\nA legal concept similar to Qisas is the principle of ''[[Eye for an eye]]'' first recorded in the [[Code of Hammurabi]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Sharia]]\n* [[Hudud]]\n* [[Tazir]]\n* [[Diyya]]\n* [[Application of sharia law by country]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Arabic words and phrases in Sharia]]\n[[Category:Islamic terminology]]\n[[Category:Islamic criminal jurisprudence]]\n[[Category:Punishments in religion]]\n[[Category:Islam and violence]]\n[[Category:Islam and capital punishment]]\n[[Category:Sharia legal terminology]]\n", "name_user": "Koreangauteng", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePakistan:Islamization in Pakistan#Qisas and Diyat Ordinance 1990", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qisas"}
{"title_page": "List of shipwrecks in April 1944", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThe '''list of shipwrecks in April 1944''' includes [[ship]]s sunk, foundered, grounded, or otherwise lost during [[April 1944]].\n{{dynamic list}}\n{{Calendar ToC}}\n==1 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=1 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Dahomian|1929|2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The cargo ship was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[South Atlantic]] {{convert|10|nmi|km}} west south west of [[Cape Point]], [[union of South Africa|South Africa]] ({{coord|34|25|S|18|19|E}}) by {{GS|U-852||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of two of her 51 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{ship|HMSAS|Krugersdorp|T48|6}} and {{ship|HMSAS|Natalia|T02|6}} (both {{navy|South Africa|1922}}).<ref name=Dahomian>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3228.html |title=Dahomian |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=22 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Jared Ingersoll||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy UGS 36]]: The [[Liberty ship]] was torpedoed and damaged in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] west of [[Algiers]], [[French Algeria|Algeria]] by [[Luftwaffe]] aircraft. She was abandoned by her crew, who were rescued by {{USS|Mills|DE-383|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). USS ''Mills'' and the tug {{HMS|Mindfull}} ({{navy|UK}}) towed the ship to Algiers where she was beached. Later repaired and returned to service.<ref name=Mills>{{cite DANFS | title = Mills | url = http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/escorts/de383.txt | accessdate = 30 January 2012 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Mantai||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[coastal trading vessel|coaster]] was sunk by gunfire and demolition charges in the [[Strait of Malacca]] by {{HMS|Truculent|P315|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=seekrieg194404/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/3514.html |title=HMS Truculent |publisher=uboat.net |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Minami Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] ({{coord|25|59|N|131|19|E}}) by {{USS|Flying Fish|SS-229|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=NorS4>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/freefleet/norfleets4.html |title=Norwegian Merchant Ships 1939 \u2013 1945, Ships beginning with So |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=7 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German submarine chaser|UJ 2127 Theodoros||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The auxiliary [[submarine chaser]] was bombed and sunk in the Mediterranean Sea by British aircraft.<ref name=seekrieg194404/> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==2 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=2 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Akebono Maru No. 3||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The transport ship was sunk in an air raid on [[Chuuk State|Truk]] by [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator]] and [[North American B-25 Mitchell]] aircraft of the United States [[Seventh Air Force]].<ref name=seekrieg194404>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wlb-stuttgart.de/seekrieg/44-04.htm |title=Seekrieg 1944, April |accessdate=7 August 2015 |last=Rohwer |first=J\u00fcrgen |authorlink=J\u00fcrgen Rohwer |author2=Gerhard H\u00fcmmelchen |work=W\u00fcrttembergische Landesbibliothek Stuttgart |publisher= |language=German }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Kaiserin Dagmar||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Denmark}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and sank in the [[Ems (river)|Ems]].<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item \n|ship={{HMS|LCA(HR) 672}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=The [[landing craft assault]] foundered during an exercise off Great Britain.<ref name=NavypediaUKLCA>{{cite web |url= http://www.navypedia.org/ships/uk/brit_aws_lcalcsm.htm |title=LCA Assault Landing Craft and LCS(M) Support Landing Craft, Royal Navy |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=ADM19440402>{{cite web |url=https://www.fold3.com/image/301350016 |title=British Admiraly War Diary, 2 April 1944 |publisher=www.fold3.com |accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item \n|ship={{HMS|LCA(HR) 811}}\n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=The [[landing craft assault]] foundered during an exercise off Great Britain.<ref name=NavypediaUKLCA/><ref name=ADM19440402/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-360||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the [[Norwegian Sea]] south west of [[Bear Island (Norway)|Bear Island]], Norway ({{Coord|72|28|N|13|04|E}}) by {{HMS|Keppel|D84|6}} ({{navy|UK}}) with the loss of all 51 crew.<ref name=U360>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u360.htm |title=U-360 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=17 March 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==3 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=3 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Fagerstrand I||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The factory ship was set on fire and severely damaged in [[K\u00e5fjord, Alta|K\u00e5fjord]] following an Allied attack on {{ship|German battleship|Tirpitz||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). The wreck was laid up, and scuttled in October 1944 by German forces. Raised in 1947, extended and returned to service in 1950 as ''Sande''.<ref name=HomeF>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/homefleet/shipsf.html |title=Norwegian Homefleet \u2013 WW II, Ships starting with F |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|I-O-78||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}} \n|desc=The ''Siebelgef\u00e4\u00df'' landing craft was sunk on this date.<ref name=\"Navypedia\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_siebelgefass.htm |title=SiebelgefaB type personnel landing craft, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=6 April 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|PiLB 425||2}}  \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The PiLB 40 type landing craft was lost on this date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_pilb40.htm |title=PiBL 40 type landing craft, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=6 April 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|StuBo 1033||2}}    \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The StuBo42 type landing craft/motor launch was sunk on this date.<ref name=\"navypedia.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_stubo42.htm |title=StuBo42 type personnel landing craft, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese guard boat|Suiten Maru||2}}  \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=The auxiliary guard boat was lost on this date.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/japan/jap_esc_aux_pc.htm |title=Auxiliary Patrol and guard boats, Japan |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=22 May 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Tosei Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[cargo liner]] was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] off the [[Nanp\u014d Islands]] by {{USS|Pollack|SS-180|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). One passenger died.<ref name=Pollack>{{cite DANFS | title = Pollack | url = http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/submar/ss180.txt | accessdate = 30 December 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hush.gooside.com/Text/3T/35To/t50321tousa.html#anchor388873 |title=Tosei Maru |publisher=hush.gooside.com |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-288||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the [[Barents Sea]] ({{coord|73|44|N|27|12|E}}) by [[Fairey Swordfish]] aircraft of [[819 Naval Air Squadron|819 Squadron]], [[Fleet Air Arm]], based on {{HMS|Activity|D94|6}} and [[Grumman TBM Avenger]] and [[Grumman F4F Wildcat]] aircraft of [[846 Naval Air Squadron|846 Squadron]], Fleet Air Arm based on {{HMS|Tracker|D24|6}} (both {{navy|UK}}) with the loss of all 49 crew.<ref name=U288>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u288.htm |title=U-288 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=14 March 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==4 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=4 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Choun Maru||2}} \n|flag={{army|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The transport was sunk in an air raid on [[Rabaul]], [[New Guinea]] by Consolidated B-24 Liberator and [[North American B-25 Mitchell]] aircraft of the United States [[Thirteenth Air Force]].<ref name=seekrieg194404/><ref name=USNChron1944>{{cite web |url=https://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USN/USN-Chron/USN-Chron-1944.html |title=USN chronology 1944 |publisher=www.ibiblio.org |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{Jsub|I-169||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The [[Kaidai-class submarine|''Kaidai''-class submarine]] was sunk in a diving accident north-west of Dublon Island, Truk, during an air raid by [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator|Consolidated PBY-4 Liberator]] aircraft. All aboard died. 32 bodies were recovered in the following weeks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/I-169.htm |title=I-169 |publisher=www.combinedfleet.com |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Iwakuni Maru||2}} \n|flag={{army|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The transport was sunk in an air raid on Rabaul by Consolidated B-25 Liberator and North American B-25 Mitchell aircraft of the United States Thirteenth Air Force. 32 crew members were killed.<ref name=seekrieg194404/><ref name=USNChron1944/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hush.gooside.com/Text/0A/02I/I80aIwa_.html |title=Iwakuni Maru |publisher=hush.gooside.com |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|I-O-10||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}} \n|desc=The ''Siebelgef\u00e4\u00df'' landing craft was sunk on this date.<ref name=\"Navypedia\"/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German minesweeper|Sperrbrecher 157||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The ''[[Sperrbrecher]]'' struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and was severely damaged off [[Brest, France|Brest]], [[Finist\u00e8re]], France.<ref name=seekrieg194404/> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==5 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=5 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese auxiliary submarine chaser|CHa-46||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The [[No.1-class auxiliary submarine chaser|''CHa-1''-class]] auxiliary [[submarine chaser]] was sunk at [[Wake Island]] by [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator]] aircraft of VB-109, [[United States Navy]].<ref name=seekrieg194404/><ref name=\"1-Go auxiliary submarine chasers\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/japan/jap_sc_aux.htm |title=1-Go auxiliary submarine chasers |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German minesweeper|R-261||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[R boat|Type R-218 minesweeper]] was sunk off [[Boulogne-sur-Mer|Boulogne]], [[Pas-de-Calais]], France by Allied aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=765 |title=German coastal minesweeper Type R-218 |publisher=Warshipsww2.Eu |accessdate=3 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140513052207/http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=756 |archive-date=13 May 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Tenryu Maru||2}} \n|flag={{army|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The transport was sunk in an air raid on Rabaul by Consolidated B-25 Liberator and North American B-25 Mitchell aircraft of the United States Thirteenth Air Force with the loss of 28 lives.<ref name=seekrieg194404/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hush.gooside.com/name/t/Te/Tenryu/Tenryu.html#anchor97346 |title=Tenryu Maru |publisher=hush.gooside.com |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German yacht|UJ 6070 Cetonia||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The armed yacht/submarine chaser was lost on this date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_conc_yachts.htm |title=Armed Yachts of WWII, Converted Merchant Ships, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=19 April 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|YT-247}} \n|flag={{navy|USA|1912}}\n|desc=The harbor tug was swamped and foundered {{convert|425|nmi|km}} south west of [[Oahu]], [[Hawaii]] ({{coord|14|14|N|158|59|E}}) while under tow from [[Pearl Harbor]] to [[Palmyra Island]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USN/USN-Chron/USN-Chron-1944.html |title=Official Cronology of the US Navy in WWII |publisher=Ibiblio |accessdate=5 April 2013}}\n</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==6 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=6 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|F 450||2}}  \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The Type C2 ''[[Marinef\u00e4hrprahm]]'' was sunk on this date.<ref name=\"MFP landing craft, Germany\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_mfp.htm |title=MFP landing craft, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=2 March 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|F 519||2}}  \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The Type B ''[[Marinef\u00e4hrprahm]]'' was heavily damaged by Allied fighter-bombers off [[Piombino]] and grounded. One crew was killed and four wounded. The wreck was then sunk in Piombino by another air attack either the 7th or the 19th.<ref name=\"MFP landing craft, Germany\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.historisches-marinearchiv.de/projekte/landungsfahrzeuge/marinefaehrprahm/ausgabe.php?where_value=556 |title=F 519 |publisher=www.historisches-marinearchiv.de |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Hsing Yun Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The transport ship struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and sank in the [[Yangtze-kiang]].<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|LCP(S) 9}}  \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=The [[LCPL|landing craft personnel (small)]] was wrecked at [[Weymouth, England]].<ref name=\"LCP, LCPS, LCPL, LCPR Landing\">{{cite web |url= http://www.navypedia.org/ships/uk/brit_aws_lcp.htm |title=LCP, LCP(S), LCP(L), LCP(R) Landing Craft, Royal Navy |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Navalhistory.net\">{{cite web |url=http://www.naval-history.net/WW2BritishLossesbyDate3.htm |title=Royal Navy vessels lost at sea Jan. '44-Nov. '45 |publisher=Navalhistory.net |accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German minesweeper|R-192||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[R boat|Type R-151 minesweeper]] was sunk in the [[Tyrrhenian Sea]] off [[Cecina, Tuscany]], Italy during a battle with [[Royal Navy]] [[motor torpedo boat]]s.<ref name=seekrieg194404/><ref name=\"Warshipsww2.Eu\">{{cite web |url=http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=764 |title=German coastal minesweeper Type R-218 |publisher=Warshipsww2.Eu |accessdate=3 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140513030230/http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=764 |archive-date=13 May 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Ruth I||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy SC 156]]: The cargo ship was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] ({{coord|45|05|N|35|11|W}}) by {{GS|U-302||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of three of her 39 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{HMS|Chelmer|K221|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=Ruth>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/singleships/ruth.html |title=D/S Ruth |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=7 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|South America|1931|2}} \n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy SC 156]]: The [[tank ship|tanker]] was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|45|04|N|35|22|W}}) by {{GS|U-302||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). All 42 crew were rescued by {{SS|Goodwin||2}} ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}).<ref name=SA>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/singleships/southamerica.html |title=M/T South America |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=7 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-302||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|45|05|N|35|11|W}}) by {{HMS|Swale|K217|6}} ({{navy|UK}}) with the loss of all 51 crew.<ref name=U302>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u302.htm |title=U-302 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=15 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-455||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] struck a mine and sank in the [[Ligurian Sea]] off [[Portofino]], [[Province of Genoa|Genoa]], Italy with the loss of all 51 crew.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Wesergau||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Norwegian Sea]] off [[Stad (peninsula)|Stad]], Norway by {{HNoMS|Ula|1943|2}} ({{navy|Norway}}).<ref name=\"Berg 1997 116\">{{Cite book|title=I skj\u00e6rg\u00e5rden og p\u00e5 havet \u2013 Marinens krig 8. april 1940 \u2013 8. mai 1945 |last=Berg |first=Ole F. |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1997 |publisher=Marinens krigsveteranforening |location=Oslo |isbn=82-993545-2-8 |page=116 |pages= |url= |language= Norwegian}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==7 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=7 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Asien||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The cargo ship was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[North Sea]] off [[Lista, Norway]] ({{coord|58|08|N|06|32|E}}) by {{HMS|Unshaken|P54|6}} ({{navy|UK}}). All her crew were saved by an escort ship.<ref name=seekrieg194404/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/3559.html |title=HMS Unshaken |publisher=uboat.net |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{Jsub|I-2||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Type J1 submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the [[Bismarck Sea]] {{convert|50|nmi|km}} west north west of [[New Hanover Island|New Hanover]], off [[Emirau Island]] ({{coord|02|17|S|149|14|E}}) by {{USS|Saufley|DD-465|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). Lost with all 111 hands.<ref name=Saufley>{{cite DANFS | title = DD-465 | url = http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/destroy/dd465txt.htm | accessdate = 21 January 2012 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Rion'' \n|flag={{flag|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=World War II: The barge struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and sank in the [[Black Sea]] ({{coord|42|11|N|41|38|E}}).<ref name=Rion>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3232.html |title=Rion |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-856||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type IX submarine|Type IX]] [[submarine]] was depth charged, shelled, rammed and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] ({{coord|40|18|N|62|22|W}}) by {{USS|Champlin|DD-601|6}} and {{USS|Huse|DE-145|6}} (both {{navy|USA|1912}}) with the loss of 27 of her 55 crew.<ref name=BI>{{cite DANFS | title = Block Island | url = http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/carriers/cve21.htm | accessdate = 12 January 2012 }}</ref><ref name=Champlin>{{cite DANFS | title = DD-601 | url = http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/destroy/dd601txt.htm | accessdate = 30 December 2011 }}</ref><ref name=U856>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/u856.htm |title=U-856 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=22 April 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==8 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=8 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese ammunition ship|Aratama Maru||2}} \n|flag={{Navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The ammunition ship was [[torpedo]]ed in the [[Pacific Ocean]] {{convert|7|nmi|km}} east of [[Guam]] ({{coord|13|16|N|145|11|E}}) by {{USS|Seahorse|SS-304|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). Her cargo of gasoline exploded damaging {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Asakaze|1922|2}} ({{navy|Empire of Japan}}). She drifted on fire for three days before coming to rest on a reef, and sinking partially submerged in shallow water, in Talafofo Bay, Guam on 11 April. Four crewmen were killed. She eventually sank completely post-war after damage by many [[typhoon]]s over a number of years.<ref name=Seahorse>{{cite DANFS | title = Seahorse | url = http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/submar/ss304.txt | accessdate = 4 January 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/Aratama_t.htm|title=Japanese Ammunition Ships |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=8 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Enco||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was sunk at [[Venice]] during an Allied air raid.<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Nebraska||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[cargo ship]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[South 