ama}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Bombay Explosion (1944)|Bombay Explosion]]: The cargo ship was severely damaged by the explosion of ''Fort Stikine'' ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}) and was declared a total loss.<ref name=Iran>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/singleships/iran.html |title=D/S Iran |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=24 January 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Jalapadna||2}} \n|flag={{flag|British India|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Bombay Explosion (1944)|Bombay Explosion]]: The ship was lifted by the [[tsunami]] caused by the explosion of ''Fort Stikine'' ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}) and broke in two when slammed down on a dock at [[Bombay]], [[British India|India]].<ref name=\"Ships lost in the Bombay explosion\"/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Kingyuan||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Bombay Explosion (1944)|Bombay Explosion]]: The ship was lost as a result of the explosion of ''Fort Stikine'' ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}) at [[Bombay]], [[British India|India]].<ref name=\"Ships lost in the Bombay explosion\"/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|LCP(L) 323}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Bombay Explosion (1944)|Bombay Explosion]]: The [[LCPL|landing craft personnel (large)]] was destroyed by the explosion of ''Fort Stikine'' ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}).<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|LCP(R) 866}}  \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Bombay Explosion (1944)|Bombay Explosion]]: The [[LCPL|landing craft personnel (ramp)]] was burnt out as a result of the explosion of ''Fort Stikine'' ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}) at [[Bombay]], [[British India|India]].<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">{{cite web |url= http://www.navypedia.org/ships/uk/brit_aws_lcp.htm |title=LCP, LCP(S), LCP(L), LCP(R) Landing Craft, Royal Navy |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Navalhistory.net\">{{cite web |url=http://www.naval-history.net/WW2BritishLossesbyDate3.htm |title=Royal Navy vessels lost at sea Jan. '44-Nov. '45 |publisher=Navalhistory.net |accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Norse Trader||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Panama}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Bombay Explosion (1944)|Bombay Explosion]]: The cargo ship was severely damaged by the explosion of ''Fort Stikine'' ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}) and was declared a total loss.<ref name=NorN>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/freefleet/norfleetn.html |title=Norwegian Merchant Ships 1939 \u2013 1945, Ships starting with N |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Rod El Farag||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Egypt}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Bombay Explosion (1944)|Bombay Explosion]]: The ship was lost as a result of the explosion of ''Fort Stikine'' ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}) at [[Bombay]], [[British India|India]].<ref name=\"Ships lost in the Bombay explosion\"/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Tinombo||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Netherlands|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Bombay Explosion (1944)|Bombay Explosion]]: The ship was burnt out as a result of the explosion of ''Fort Stikine'' ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}) at [[Bombay]], [[British India|India]]. Declared a total loss, she was sunk for use as a jetty.<ref name=\"Ships lost in the Bombay explosion\"/><ref name=Jordan452>{{cite book |title=The world's merchant fleets, 1939 |first=Roger |last=Jordan |publisher=Chatham publishing |location=London |year=1999 |page=452 |isbn=1 86176 023 X}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-448||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] was [[depth charged]] and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] north east of the [[Azores]], Portugal ({{coord|46|22|N|19|35|W}}) by {{HMS|Pelican|L86|6}} ({{navy|UK}}) and {{HMCS|Swansea|K328|6}} ({{navy|Canada|1911}}) with the loss of nine 