y|USA|1912}}). USS ''Mills'' and the tug {{HMS|Mindfull}} ({{navy|UK}}) towed the ship to Algiers where she was beached. Later repaired and returned to service.<ref name=Mills>{{cite DANFS | title = Mills | url = http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/escorts/de383.txt | accessdate = 30 January 2012 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Mantai||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[coastal trading vessel|coaster]] was sunk by gunfire and demolition charges in the [[Strait of Malacca]] by {{HMS|Truculent|P315|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=seekrieg194404/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/3514.html |title=HMS Truculent |publisher=uboat.net |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Minami Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] ({{coord|25|59|N|131|19|E}}) by {{USS|Flying Fish|SS-229|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=NorS4>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/freefleet/norfleets4.html |title=Norwegian Merchant Ships 1939 \u2013 1945, Ships beginning with So |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=7 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German submarine chaser|UJ 2127 Theodoros||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The auxiliary [[submarine chaser]] was bombed and sunk in the Mediterranean Sea by British aircraft.<ref name=seekrieg194404/> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==2 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=2 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Akebono Maru No. 3||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The transport ship was sunk in an air raid on [[Chuuk State|Truk]] by [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator]] and [[North American B-25 Mitchell]] aircraft of the United States [[Seventh Air Force]].<ref name=seekrieg194404>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wlb-stuttgart.de/seekrieg/44-04.htm |title=Seekrieg 1944, April |accessdate=7 August 2015 |last=Rohwer |first=J\u00fcrgen |authorlink=J\u00fcrgen Rohwer |author2=Gerhard H\u00fcmmelchen |work=W\u00fcrttembergische Landesbibliothek Stuttgart |publisher= |language=German }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Kaiserin Dagmar||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Denmark}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and sank in the [[Ems (river)|Ems]].<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item \n|ship={{HMS|LCA(HR) 672}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=The [[landing craft assault]] foundered during an exercise off Great Britain.<ref name=NavypediaUKLCA>{{cite web |url= http://www.navypedia.org/ships/uk/brit_aws_lcalcsm.htm |title=LCA Assault Landing Craft and LCS(M) Support Landing Craft, Royal Navy |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=ADM19440402>{{cite web |url=https://www.fold3.com/image/301350016 |title=British Admiraly War Diary, 2 April 1944 |publisher=www.fold3.com |accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item \n|ship={{HMS|LCA(HR) 811}}\n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=The [[landing craft assault]] foundered during an exercise off Great Britain.<ref name=NavypediaUKLCA/><ref name=ADM19440402/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-360||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the [[Norwegian Sea]] south west of [[Bear Island (Norway)|Bear Island]], Norway ({{Coord|72|28|N|13|04|E}}) by {{HMS|Keppel|D84|6}} ({{navy|UK}}) with the loss of all 51 crew.<ref name=U360>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u360.htm |title=U-360 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=17 March 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==3 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=3 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Fagerstrand I||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The factory ship was set on fire and severely damaged in [[K\u00e5fjord, Alta|K\u00e5fjord]] following an Allied attack on {{ship|German battleship|Tirpitz||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). The wreck was laid up, and scuttled in October 1944 by German forces. Raised in 1947, extended and returned to service in 1950 as ''Sande''.<ref name=HomeF>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/homefleet/shipsf.html |title=Norwegian Homefleet \u2013 WW II, Ships starting with F |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|I-O-78||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}} \n|desc=The ''Siebelgef\u00e4\u00df'' landing craft was sunk on this date.<ref name=\"Navypedia\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_siebelgefass.htm |title=SiebelgefaB type personnel landing craft, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=6 April 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|PiLB 425||2}}  \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The PiLB 40 type landing craft was lost on this date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_pilb40.htm |title=PiBL 40 type landing craft, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=6 April 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|StuBo 1033||2}}    \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The StuBo42 type landing craft/motor launch was sunk on this date.<ref name=\"navypedia.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_stubo42.htm |title=StuBo42 type personnel landing craft, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese guard boat|Suiten Maru||2}}  \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=The auxiliary guard boat was lost on this date.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/japan/jap_esc_aux_pc.htm |title=Auxiliary Patrol and guard boats, Japan |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=22 May 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Tosei Maru||2}} \n|flag