aul Hamilton'' exploding]]World War II: Convoy UGS 38: The [[Liberty ship]] was torpedoed, blew up and sank in the Mediterranean Sea off Algiers ({{coord|37|00|N|3|20|E}}) by aircraft of III ''Staffeln'', ''Kampfgeschwader 26'' and I & II ''Staffeln'', ''Kampfgeschwader 77'', Luftwaffe. All 504 troops, 29 gunners and 47 crewmen aboard were killed.<ref name=seekrieg194404/><ref name=LibP>{{cite web |url=http://www.mariners-l.co.uk/LibShipsP.html |title=Liberty Ships \u2013 P |publisher=Mariners |accessdate=6 January 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Rogaland|1929|2}} \n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 101I-117-0353-29, Norwegen, Bergen, Motorschiff \"Rogaland\".jpg|thumb|''Rogaland'']]\n[[Explosion in Bergen 1944|Bergen explosion]]: The cargo ship was sunk at Bergen by the explosion of {{Ship|ST|Voorbode||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). Raised later that year and laid up at [[\u00d8lesund]]. Repaired and returned to service in 1947.<ref name=seekrieg194404/><ref name=HomeR>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/homefleetsingles/rogaland.html |title=D/S Rogaland |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Royal Star||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: Convoy UGS 38: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] northeast of [[Algiers]], [[Algeria]] ({{coord|37|02|N|3|41|E}}) by aircraft of the Luftwaffe. One crew member was lost.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bluestarline.org/royal1.html |title=Royal Star |publisher=www.bluestarline.org |accessdate=20 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German minesweeper|Sperrbrecher 102 Condor||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The ''[[Sperrbrecher]]'' was torpedoed and sunk in the North Sea off [[Schiermonnikoog]], [[Friesland]], Netherlands by Allied aircraft.<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|UIT-5||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The submarine was sunk at [[Monfalcone]], [[Friuli-Venezia-Giulia]], Italy in an Allied air raid.<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German submarine chaser|UJ 203||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[submarine chaser]], a former {{sclass-|Gabbiano|corvette}}, was sunk at Monfalcone by Allied aircraft.<ref name=\"WarshipsWW2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=1226 |title=German Sub Chasers Captured Italian |publisher=WarshipsWW2 |accessdate=6 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808053133/http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=1226 |archive-date=8 August 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> She was further attacked and destroyed on 19 July 1944.<ref name=seekrieg194407>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wlb-stuttgart.de/seekrieg/44-07.htm |title=Seekrieg 1944, Juli |accessdate=5 September 2015 |last=Rohwer |first=J\u00fcrgen |authorlink=J\u00fcrgen Rohwer |author2=Gerhard H\u00fcmmelchen  |work=W\u00fcrttembergische Landesbibliothek Stuttgart |publisher= |language=German }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|ST|Voorbode||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=[[Explosion in Bergen 1944|Bergen explosion]]: The ammunition transport was sunk off Bergen by an accidental explosion. One hundred and fifty-eight people were killed. About 4,800 were wounded. }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==21 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=21 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=[[HNLMS Abraham van der Hulst (1937)|''M-553'']] \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The {{sclass-|Jan van Amstel|minesweeper|1}} struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and sank in the [[Baltic Sea]] off the coast of [[East Prussia]]. She was later raised.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=793 |title=German Minesweepers Netherlandish |publisher=Warshipsww2.Eu |a