oed and sunk in the [[Strait of Malacca]] by {{HMS|Taurus|P399|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|ST|Kainan Maru No. 15||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[tugboat|tug]] was torpedoed and sunk in the Strait of Malacca by {{HMS|Taurus|P399|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese transport|Koryu Maru||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: Convoy SHISA-17: The transport was bombed and sunk in the [[South China Sea]] {{convert|2|nmi|km}} north east of Cape St. Jacques Lighthouse, [[French Indochina]], by [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator]] aircraft of the 308th Bomb Group, United States [[Fourteenth Air Force]]. Thirty-eight troops and 43 crewmen were killed.<ref name=\"Japanese Transports\">{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/Nagata_t.htm |title=Japanese Transports |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=22 April 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese transport|London Maru||2}} \n|flag={{army|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: Convoy SHISA-17: The ''London Maru''-class transport was bombed and sunk in the South China Sea {{convert|2|nmi|km}} north east of Cape St. Jacques Lighthouse, French Indochina, by Consolidated B-24 Liberator aircraft of the 308th Bomb Group, United States Fourteenth Air Force. Two crewmen were killed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/Nagata_t.htm |title=Japanese Army Auxiliary Transports |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=22 April 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese transport|Nagata Maru||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: Convoy SHISA-17: The ''Ikuta Maru''-class transport was bombed and sunk in the South China Sea {{convert|2|nmi|km}} north east of Cape St. Jacques Lighthouse, French Indochina, by Consolidated B-24 Liberator aircraft of the 308th Bomb Group, United States Fourteenth Air Force. Nineteen troops, 27 other passengers, and seven crewmen were killed.<ref name=\"Japanese Transports\"/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Soviet cargo ship|Pavlin Vinogradov||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=World War II: During a voyage with a cargo of [[acetone]] from [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]], to [[Vladivostok]] in the [[Soviet Union]] via [[Akutan, Alaska|Akutan]] in the [[Aleutian Islands]], the 2,864-[[gross register ton]] [[cargo liner]] was sunk by an unidentified [[submarine]] \u2013 almost certainly {{Jsub|I-180||2}} ({{navy|Empire of Japan}}) \u2013 in the [[North Pacific Ocean]] approximately {{convert|250|nmi}} southeast of [[Dutch Harbor, Alaska|Dutch Harbor]], [[Territory of Alaska]]. She exploded and sank in less than a minute, with 13 crewmen killed. The other 29 crewmen abandoned ship in a [[Lifeboat (shipboard)|lifeboat]], but only nine of them remained alive when the [[Steamship|steamer]] ''Ola'' ({{flag|Soviet Union}}) rescued them six days later. ''Pavlin Vinogradov''{{'}}s [[Sea captain|master]] did not survive.<ref name=alaskashipwrecksp>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-p/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (P)]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shipsnostalgia.com/guides/Soviet_Merchant_Marine_Losses_in_WW2_%28Black_Sea%2C_Caspian_and_Pacific%29  |title=Soviet Marine Losses in WWII (Pacific Ocean)|publisher=Shipnostalgia.com |accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German minelayer|Roland||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The auxiliary [[minelayer]] struck a mine and sank in the Baltic Sea.<ref name=seekrieg194403>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wlb-stuttgart.de/seekrieg/44-03.htm |title=Seekrieg 1944, M\u00e4rz |accessdate=3 August 2015 |last=Rohwer |first=J\u00fcrgen |authorlink=J\u00fcrgen Rohwer |author2=Gerhard H\u00fcmmelchen |work=W\u00fcrttembergische Landesbibliothek Stuttgart |publisher= |language=German 